<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian Former Prime Minister Commits Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Official source in the Syrian
Interior Ministry on Sunday confirmed that former Syrian prime
minister Mahmoud Zouebi committed suicide by shooting himself with
a handgun when a senior police officer went to his house to meet
him.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued to the Syrian News Agency, the source said
that under an order issued by the economic investigation judge, the
police chief in Damascus went to Zouebi's house in Dumur district
near Damascus to tell him to stand before the judge for
investigation over charges of abusing power and damaging the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
When the police chief asked for meeting Zouebi, he heard the
sound of gun firing and soon came to know that Zouebi committed
suicide by shooting himself in his room, the source added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Zouebi was immediately taken to a hospital in
Damascus for emergency treatment, but he was dead.
</P>
<P>
Zouebi, 62, held premiership for 13 years. During the last two
years of his office, the cabinet was widely accused of corruption
and
bribery. A new cabinet was later formed under Mohammed Mustafa
Miro.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to Zouebi family said since he was fired from the
ruling Arab Baath Socialist Party and declaring and tried by a
Syrian court, Zouebi has been suffering from nerves breakdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
