<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Jews Accused of Spying for Iraq: Iranian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian judiciary official on
Monday denied reports that some of the Iranian Jews being tried for
spying for Israel were also accused of spying for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
All the 13 Jews being tried are solely charged of spying for
Israel, and none of them have been accused of spying for Iraq, said
Hossein Ali Amiri, head of justice department in the southern Fars
Province, where the accused are being tried.
</P>
<P>
The official termed the report by AFP on Sunday as "baseless".
The AFP report was based on a statement by two French lawyers who
have been sent to Iran by the Lawyers Without Borders to follow the
trial, which has caused international concern, even protests by
Jewish communities in Western countries.
</P>
<P>
The trial of the 13 Jews by a revolutionary court opened on
April 13. So far seven secret court hearings have been held and 10
of the suspects have reportedly admitted having connections with
Israel's security service.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews were arrested more than a year ago along with eight
Muslims accused of the same crimes. Currently the eight Muslims and
three of the Jews are free on bail.
</P>
<P>
However, the judiciary official said on Monday that five of the
freed suspects, both Muslims and Jews, have appeared before the
revolutionary court in Shiraz, Fars Province and responded to the
charges against them in recent days following a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
The court has also summoned other suspects freed on bail and
they are required to appear before the court three days after
receiving the order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
