<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemenis Mark Unity Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Yemenis on Monday
celebrated the tenth anniversary of the country's Unity Declaration
at the Sabe'ini Square in capital Sanaa with a military parade and
athletic shows.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh and other top officials
attended the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the gathering, Yemeni Prime Minister Abdul-Karim al-
Iryani said unity would remain as the source of strength for Arab
and Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
"Unity of Yemen will remain an important factor of security and
stability in the region," Iryani said, adding that "Yemen has an
unshakable conviction that Arab solidarity and unity of ranks are a
prerequisite to face current and future challenges."
</P>
<P>
Yemen will continue calling on Arab countries to set aside their
past differences, with visions for forging closer inter-Arab ties
and for Arab joint action so as to face the challenges and
developments of the time, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The festivities were also attended by foreign guests, including
the Chinese delegation headed by Deputy Chairman of the National
People's Congress Timor Dwamat.
</P>
<P>
Yemen was divided for centuries and ruled by monarchies and
local
tribes until the 1960s. On May 22, 1990, Yemen Arab Republic and
People's Democratic Republic of Yemen were united as the Republic
of Yemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
