<HEADLINE> Building of New Jewish Neighborhood in Abu Dis Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Jerusalem Municipal Planning
and Building Committee approved on Monday a plan for building a
Jewish neighborhood in Abu Dis, a Palestinian village east of the
Old City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Seven committee members voted in favor of the plan, while only
one against.
</P>
<P>
The plan, encompassing 200 home units, is to be submitted to the
Regional Planning and Building Committee for approval.
</P>
<P>
With the approval by the regional committee, the municipality
will be able to draw up a more conclusive plan for the neighborhood
construction.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Jerusalem Mayor Shmuel Shakedi of the National Religious
Party called the decision "historic" and added that whoever favors
Jewish-Arab coexistence should be happy with it.
</P>
<P>
But other peace groups in Israel called the decision a political
one, saying that it proves that Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert, a
member of the opposition Likud party, is trying to force the
government to accept his own political agenda.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dis is one of the three Palestinian villages near Jerusalem
that the government decided to hand over to the Palestinians. The
transfer has been delayed due to violent clashes in recent days in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Knesset approved the transfer of the three villages
last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Building Jewish houses in Abu Dis will be a sensitive issue and
it will cause more conflicts between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
