<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian President Urges Annan to End Ethiopian- Eritrean Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Abdul-Aziz
Bouteflika called on U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan on Monday to
exert more efforts to halt the ongoing atrocities between Ethiopia
and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
In a message sent to Annan, Bouteflika, who is currently
rotating president of the Organization of African Unity(OAU), said
he discussed with the U.N. chief on May 5 the possibility of
resumption of the armed conflict between the two African countries.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, according to the message, his concerns came true
on May 12 and the military confrontation between Ethiopia and
Eritrea is escalating despite the efforts of the OAU and the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"In the name of the OAU, I have issued several appeals to the
leaders of the two warring countries to ceasefire and resume the
peace talks. For the same purpose, I sent my personal envoy to the
capitals of the two countries on May 21," Bouteflika said.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the armed conflict is escalating forces me to
admit that the OAU efforts are not able solely to stop the sounds
of weapons, stop the bloodshed and return the two warring sides to
the negotiating table," he said.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea broke off on May
10 and the Ethiopian forces intruded into the Eritrean boder towns,
forcing thousands of civilians to flee from the western areas to
the capital city of Asmara.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than half a million Eritrean people face a
humanitarian catastrophe due to insufficient human relief supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
