<HEADLINE> Annan Warns U.S. Senator's Blocking Peacekeeping Funds Could Hamper U.N. Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday warned that the blocking of U.N. peacekeeping funds
by one U.S. Senator was going to hamper U.N. activities and the U.
N. ability to have the resources required to carry on its mandated
functions.
</P>
<P>
Annan said, "The holds are against four peacekeeping operations
and today. I will be making a proposal to the Council that may
introduce another operation on southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"And of course, if all these holds continue, it is going to
hamper our activities and our ability to have the resources
required to carry on our mandated functions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So I hope that the other members of the Senate would work with
the Senator concerned to remove their holds," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator Judd Gregg of New Hampshire has blocked for
several months 368 million U.S. dollars that the United States
owes the U.N. to support peacekeeping operations in Sierra Leone,
Kosovo, East Timor and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The United States has already owed the United Nations 1.7
billion dollars, of which 1.1 billion is for peacekeeping debts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
