<HEADLINE> Reppas on Proposal for Withdrawal of Turkish Aegean Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- What is of interest is the foreign
policy exercised by Turkey in practice, the improvement of the
Greek-Turkish relations and the establishment of a new cooperation
relationship between the two neighboring countries, Greek
government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reppas made the remarks when commenting on the proposal by
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's adviser for the abolition
of the Turkish "Aegean Army" and the adoption of a policy of
mutual concessions on Greek-Turkish issues.
</P>
<P>
The senior Turkish military aide also proposed Ecevit's
referral of the Aegean continental shelf issue to international
arbitration or a "freeze" on the issue, the Turkish daily "Sabah"
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that Greece had no reason to comment on articles
or views expressed by different officials.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Aegean Army, which is deployed in Izmir, is created
following Greece's intentions to extend its territorial waters to
12 nautical miles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
