<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela To Allow Private Gas Exploitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's Ministry of Energy and
Mines will begin in June the bidding process for granting to
private firms 11 areas for gas exploration and production.
</P>
<P>
These developments of "non-associated" gas, that is, not
subject to petroleum exploitation, will require an investment of 2
billion U.S. dollars during 15 years, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's reserves of free and associated gas are over 142
billion cubic feet, equivalent to 25 billion barrels of crude oil,
placing this country among the seven main world producing
countries.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of these reserves is made up by gas associated
with crude production.
</P>
<P>
The Organic Law of Gaseous Hydrocarbons of Venezuela allows
exploring and producing of gas by national or foreign private
companies, with or without state participation.
</P>
<P>
But in the case of non-associated gas, a license on behalf of
the Ministry of Energy and Mines is required, and permits will be
granted in the coming December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
