<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Help Nigeria Carry Out Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has pledged to provide
80 million U.S. dollars to Nigeria to support its educational and
economic reforms, reports reaching here quoted an agreement as
saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed Monday by Jubirl
Martins-Kuye, Nigeria' s Minister of State for Finance and the
visiting World Bank's President for Africa Callisto Madavo, the
loans will go to areas of education, water supply, and
transparency-fostering of the government's economic management.
</P>
<P>
Martins-Kuye said after the signing ceremony that the
revitalization of education, would help "attack poverty at the
base to ensure that future generations of Nigerians become more
productive and free from the shackles of ignorance".
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
launched a universal education promotion program in a bid to boost
primary school enrolment among the reported 3.8 million children,
who are out of school due to poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
