<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Grand Imam Calls for Reconciliation, Peace in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's most prestigious cleric, Grand
Imam of Al-Azhar Mohamed Sayed Tantawi, on Monday called on Somali
factions to seek ways of ending war and realizing national
reconciliation and peace, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The civil war has destroyed state institutions and the economy
of Somalia and resulted in displacement of hundreds of thousands of
people, who face oppression and tyranny, Tantawi said in a message
to Djiboutian Foreign Minister Ali Abdi Fareh. Djibouti is hosting
a Somali reconciliation conference.
</P>
<P>
A group of influential people exploited the war for more
influence and wealth at the expense of innocent children and women,
Tantawi said, adding that such chaotic situation would provide
foreign powers with the opportunity to tear up Somalia for their
expansionist interests.
</P>
<P>
"Sincere Somalis and their Arab and Muslim brothers should
cooperate in order to achieve the peace aims," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been in division since 1991 when the former
president, Siad Barre, was toppled. Djiboutian President Ismael
Omar Guelleh proposed last year an initiative, calling on the
Somali warlords to disarm, turn their factions into political
parties, and to submit to the authority of a formal legal system.
</P>
<P>
Under this peace plan, a Somali reconciliation conference opened
in Djibouti on May 2. Some 460 representatives of the civil
society, including university professors, intellectuals, writers
and tribal leaders took part in the gathering. Representatives of
the United Nations, the Organization of African Unity, the European
Union, Egypt and the United States also attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Iman described the Somali peace conference as "a
precious opportunity for Somalia and its people to pass out of the
debacle."
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate the efforts exerted by Djibouti for this noble
end. All Arab and Islamic countries must support Djibouti in order
to achieve this aim," Tantawi said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Azhar is Egypt's leading Muslim authority and the highest
seat of Sunni Islamic studies in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's leading oil producer Altinyag firm has
started trade with Greece, reported Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Altinyag General Director Ramazan Abay said in Izmir, southwest
Turkey, on Monday that his company will export 3,000 tons of
sunflower oil to Greece and in return import 2,000 tons of soybean
oil from Greece every month.
</P>
<P>
The project was initiated by Izmir Trade Chamber, said Abay. The
first oil transfer from Turkey to Greece was made on Monday by a
ship which will make weekly trips to carry oil between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Greek firms used to purchase oil from France, however, they
began to turn to Turkey due to the geographical closeness of the
two countries as well as the reasonable prices of Altinyag.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Tourism Ministry has worked out a plan for
2000-2005, which is designed to raise the annual tourism revenues
to 10 billion U.S. dollars from the current 4.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Mamdouh Beltagui told the Economic Committee of
the ruling National Democratic Party that his ministry plans to
raise the number of visitors to 9.5 million from the present 5.4
million in a year, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Higher rate of revenues and tourist influx will in turn create
800,000 job opportunities each year, Beltagui said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian and Moroccan businessmen agreed on Monday to
set up two joint projects in Casablanca and Port Said, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Joint Egyptian-Moroccan Chamber of Commerce
Gamal Abu Emera said that the businessmen will set up a clothes
factory in Casablanca that will use Egyptian cotton as raw
material.
</P>
<P>
They will set up a sardine factory in the free zone in Port Said
that will benefit from the Moroccan expertise in this domain, Abu
Emera said.
</P>
<P>
The total capital of the two projects is estimated at 15 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt urged the World Health Organization (WHO) to
begin a new initiative to give poor countries access to medical
equipment and medicine, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody can deny the poor their right to medical treatment,"
Minister of Health and Population Ismail Sallam said Sunday upon
his return from a WHO conference in Geneva. He stressed that
medical treatment is a basic human right, and demanded that WHO
establish a higher committee to make medicine accessible to poor
countries.
</P>
