<HEADLINE> Moroccan King in Cairo to Seek Closer Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Moroccan King Mohammed VI arrived in
Cairo Monday evening for the first state visit. Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak greeted the king at Cairo International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Following a red-carpet reception, Mubarak and Mohammed VI went
into a one-on-one meeting, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported. They were expected to discuss regional issues and
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During Mohammad VI's three-day visit, the fourth session of the
Egyptian-Moroccan Higher Committee will be held under the co-
chairmanship of the two leaders, the news agency said. A number of
agreements will be signed during the session to promote cooperation
in various fields between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Morocco formed the joint committee in 1997. Since
then, their trade volume has risen by 85 percent to 37 million U.S.
dollars in 1999 from 20 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The two countries hope to enhance the volume to an annual 100
million dollars in light of the free trade agreement signed in
April, 1999. They have a vision to raise the trade volume to 1
billion dollars in 2010.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two leaders will hold talks to discuss issues
related to the Arab world, the latest developments in the Middle
East peace process on all tracks and the situation in the region,
it added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also review the outcome of the Africa-Europe
summit held in April in the Egyptian capital. 
</P>
