<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Hopes to Enhance Cooperation With Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is keen on enhancing
cooperation with Iraq in industrial, trade, economic, scientific
and artistic fields, said visiting Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister of Economy Petar Zhotev here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Iraqi-Bulgarian Joint Committee meetings, which
started on Monday, Zhotev said Bulgaria hopes to establish long-
term cooperation with Iraq, as Bulgaria has also suffered economic
losses due to the U.N. embargo imposed on Iraq since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria wishes to enhance trade ties with Iraq through the
joint committee meetings, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Zhotev, heading an 80-member delegation, arrived in the Iraqi
capital Baghdad late Sunday to attend the 24th session of the
Iraqi-Bulgarian Joint Committee, the official Iraqi News Agency
(INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Iraqi Minister of Industry and Minerals Adnan
Abdal-Majid al-Ani expressed the hope that Iraq and Bulgaria can
develop a mechanism for improving bilateral trade and economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
Terming Bulgaria as "a friendly country," the Iraqi minister
said the two countries enjoyed good relations before the imposition
of the U.N. embargo against Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to establish three new subcommittees
of trade, finance and science subordinate to the joint committee as
a means of promoting bilateral cooperation, said the INA.
</P>
<P>
The last round of the joint committee meetings were held in the
Bulgarian capital Sofia in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the Bulgarian deputy prime minister came amid
mounting international pressure for lifting the U.N. embargo on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, as a trading partner of Iraq, is eagerly vying for a
slice of Iraq's lucrative reconstruction market of about 200
billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
