<HEADLINE> Romania to Plant 2 Million Hectares with Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Environment Ministry
unveiled recently a national program for planting nearly 2 million
hectares of land with forest over 50 years at a recent meeting of
the United Nations Convention on the desertification of land
affected by drought and deterioration.
</P>
<P>
"It is an ambitious program which calls for planting an annual
10,000 to 40,000 hectares with forest on deteriorated land, so as
to expand Romania's forested land by 2 million hectares," Gheorghe
Laza, secretary general of the Ministry of Waters, Forests and
Environment Protection, told the press Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Environment Ministry officials are currently implementing a
government resolution aimed to set up a specialized national
committee that will include experts and members of such national
institutions as the National Meteorological Institute and the
Forestry Research Institute. The committee plans to pursue a
national strategy and action plan for deteriorated land, due to be
finalized by this September.
</P>
<P>
The Environment Ministry officials want the document to be
presented by the Romanian delegation to the 4th meeting of the
United Nations Convention due to be held in Australia over
September 25-October 7. 
</P>
