<HEADLINE> Mobile Licenses Boost For Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Mobile phone operators are facing an
85 billion pound bill to buy next-generation licenses which could
give an unexpected boost to the flagging euro.
</P>
<P>
The figure, calculated by economists in J.P. Morgan is several
times larger than previously estimated because European
governments are opting to auction their licenses rather than
assign them after contests.
</P>
<P>
The British newspaper, The Times, said Monday that Germany,
France, Italy, The Netherlands and Belgium are all keen to
replicate the success of Britain's license auction, which raised
22.5 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
The countries are all expected to hold auctions over the next
12 months. Spain and Finland have already completed their
preparation for the contests.
</P>
<P>
According to J.P. Morgan, the vast transfer of funds from the
private sector to the public sector could help to move the budget
position of euroland from a deficit of 0.4 percent of GDP to a
surplus next year of 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Brown, the British chancellor, has indicated that he
will use the proceeds of Britain's license auction to reduce the
national debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
