war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"It is basically to get their support for the ongoing peace
process and to explain that they will have the opportunity to make
recommendations on the draft program (for the peace process)," a
spokeswoman of Mandela's office said.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the talks were representatives of the Party for
the Liberation of the Hutu People (PALIPEHUTU) and Front for
National Liberation (FROLINA), said the spokeswoman Zelda Le
Grange.
</P>
<P>
So far the meetings have been "very positive, very fruitful",
said the spokeswoman, adding the rebel representatives were "all
committed to driving the peace process as quickly as possible".
</P>
<P>
Mandela, chief mediator in Burundi's peace process, will on
Tuesday hold separate talks with representatives of another three
rebel groups and of Burundian government.
</P>
<P>
War broke out in 1993 in Burundi, pitting several rebel Hutu
factions against the Tutsi-dominated government and army. Some
200,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed in the savage
wars between them.
</P>
<P>
The current talks in South Africa mediated by Mandela is
expected to focus on a ceasefire between the warring sides, and
the integration of the rebels into a new national army. 
</P>
