at Bayet Yahoon in south Lebanon, ANN television station reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hezbollah guerrillas, who have been leading a war to
oust Israeli occupation forces and the the pro-Israeli SLA from
south Lebanon, also captured ten SLA militiamen who refused to
surrender or withdraw at the position of Houla, local radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, nearly a thousand Lebanese returned to the five
villages evacuated by the SLA in south Lebanon. Hundreds of them
swarmed into the village of Toyeebat with dozens of armed Hezbollah
members.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded and occupied south Lebanon in 1978 and set up a
security zone there in 1985 with a self-claimed aim of protecting
its northern settlements from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel began its withdrawal from south Lebanon earlier
this month, dozens of SLA militiamen have deserted, many of them
surrendering to the resistance guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
As Israel promised to pull out all its forces from south Lebanon
by July, the fate of the SLA militiamen has drawn more and more
world attention. Both the Lebanese government troops and Hezbollah
have announced that they will not forgive the militiamen who
betrayed their country and will bring them to trial. 
