<HEADLINE> U.S., British Bombings Injure 1 Civilian in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- One Iraqi civilian was injured
Monday during air raids by U.S. and British warplanes on southern
Iraq, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
the spokesman said that at 8:55 local time (0455 GMT), five
formations of U.S. and British planes coming from Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait made 10 armed sorties over southern Iraq, bombing civilian
and service installations.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that at 11:30 (0730 GMT), nine hostile
formations from Turkey made 15 armed sorties over northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On both occasions, Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery intercepted
these planes, forcing them to flee back to their bases in Turkey,
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the total number of sorties made by
the U.S. and British jets have reached 21,289 since December 1998
when the U.S. and Britain launched the four-night fierce air
attacks against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British planes have been patrolling the two so-
called no-fly zones, set up by the two powers after the 1991 Gulf
War to, as they said, provide aerial protection from the Iraqi
government forces for Kurds in the north and Shiite Muslims in the
south.
</P>
<P>
Iraq does not recognize the zones, which are not specifically
covered by any U.N. resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
