<HEADLINE> Israel Would Launch Reprisals if Northern Israel Attacked: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
warned again on Monday that if Israel is attacked after its troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon, the Israeli military will launch
reprisals not to be limited to the border area.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the northern border town of Zarit, Barak said the
reprisal will be in entirely different places, which will prove
very painful.
</P>
<P>
"I don't recommend to anyone in the area to provoke a response
from Israel," Barak added.
</P>
<P>
Barak repeated the warning as the situation in south Lebanon and
as in northern Israel has become even more tense, as the Israeli-
backed South Lebanon Army (SLA) abandoned on Monday all the
outposts in central security zone and two outposts in the western
sector.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of local Lebanese Shi'ite Muslims, some of them
Hezbollah activists, reportedly poured into the abandoned outposts
and nearby villages, throwing the security zone Israel has occupied
for years into chaos.
</P>
<P>
Israeli helicopters opened fire and killed at least two local
Lebanese civilians, apparently trying to scare them from entering
the abandoned places.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SLA soldiers and their families crowed around some of
the crossings on the Lebanese-Israeli border on Monday and the
Israel Defense Force (IDF) is coordinating their entrance into
Israel.
</P>
<P>
To study the tense situation in south Lebanon and along the
northern border, Barak visited the north on Monday together with
top IDF officers.
</P>
<P>
For fear of possible Hezbollah guerrillas attacks, the IDF
ordered residents of northern Israel into bomb shelters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Israeli Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh also went to the
north on Monday and warned that any Hezbollah attacks after a
withdrawal will prompt Israel to send forces back into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"If anyone wants to avert the need for us to go in again, the
way to do that is to keep Hezbollah away from the border," Sneh
told SLA militiamen who fled to northern Israel earlier on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sneh said Israel is prepared to offer political asylum to SLA
members and their families and have already put aside apartments to
house them.
</P>
<P>
Israel is coordinating its withdrawal with the United Nations,
which plans to expand its peacekeeping forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, the main military group fighting
Israeli occupation since Israel set up the security zone in 1985,
is following hard on the heels of the Israeli pullback and
inflicting heavy casualties on the SLA.
</P>
<P>
Barak promised to bring the IDF home from south Lebanon by July
7. But the situation there could force Barak to order an early
withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
