<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Continue Supporting Federation in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. will continue to support a
bizonal, bicommunal federation formula in Cyprus, said U.S.
Ambassador to Cyprus Donald Bandler here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue will be resolved by the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot leaders "with some help from their friends," said Bandler
after meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
However, "we do not have a plan to solve the Cyprus problem that
is going to be imposed on anyone," Bandler was quoted as saying by
the Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the next round of U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks on Cyprus will be upgraded and will lend itself to
a meaningful negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Bandler made the pledge apparently to address concerns by some
local political leaders about U.S. President Bill Clinton's remarks
to some Greek American leaders last week on two entities in Cyprus
and the right of free movement on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern part of the island after a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
In efforts to solve the Cyprus issue, two rounds of U.N.-
sponsored talks have been held so far, during which the two sides
presented and elaborated on their positions.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks have been scheduled to start on July 5
in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Bandler also said that he had "good meeting" with President
Clerides, who looked in excellent form, three weeks after
undergoing an operation to remove a polyp from his large intestine.
</P>
</TEXT>
