<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Northern Residents Ordered into Bomb Shelters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Israel Defense Forces (IDF)
ordered about 200,000 residents in Israel's northern communities
along the border with Lebanon to lock themselves into bomb shelters
late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The order was prompted by IDF's pessimistic evaluation on the
tense situation in the zone and intelligence information that
Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas may launch reprisal attacks against
these settlements, army sources revealed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Israel Air Force fighter planes and attack
helicopters reportedly killed two Lebanese civilians and wounded at
least seven others in an aerial assault in the occupied security
zone, a buffer area set up by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed
aim to prevent cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The two were among hundreds of Lebanese, most of them Hezbollah
supporters, who were marching into the zone to reclaim their homes
in several villages, which they left behind after Israel's
occupation two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The villagers decided to return on news that the Israeli-backed
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militiamen had abandoned their positions
in these villages and fled with their families to Israeli border to
seek asylum.
</P>
<P>
The IDF, in carrying out the Israeli cabinet's resolution in
March to pull out of south Lebanon by July, had transferred some
outposts to SLA, hoping the militia would control these abandoned
areas and act as buffer forces for some time.
</P>
<P>
However, the proxy group, which depends upon Israel's ammunition
supply and air force backup, collapsed faster and more disorderly
than IDF had thought, according to some military analysts.
</P>
<P>
It appeared now that the Hezbollah, a Shiite Muslim guerrilla
group which has been fighting against Israeli occupation in south
Lebanon for decades, will fill the vacuum left by Israeli and SLA
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The approaching of the Hezbollah made Israeli northern residents
really worried about their future security as their communities had
been hit by Hezbollah's Katyusha rockets time and time again during
the years.
</P>
<P>
The latest of such attacks took place in early May, when several
waves of Katyusha rockets landed in these communities, wounding
civilians, damaging properties and triggering fire.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, speaking at the border town
of Zarit on Monday, warned again that if Israeli north is attacked
after its troops pullback from south Lebanon, the IDF will launch a
reprisal not to be limited to the border area.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear whether the rapidly deteriorating
situation will force the IDF to move up its redeployment plan to
early June, as some media reports had speculated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
