<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls for Respect for Freedom, Civil Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
stressed here on Monday that the people's legitimate freedom and
civil rights must be respected as they are the basis of national
security.
</P>
<P>
Everyone living in the country should observe the Constitution,
which specifies that everybody enjoys legitimate freedom and civil
rights, Khatami said in an address marking the third anniversary of
his landslide victory in the presidential election on May 23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the election, reform-minded Khatami defeated his conservative
rival, current Majlis (parliament) Speaker Ali Netaq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Khatami has been promoting his social and political
reform programs, including easing Islamic restrictions on personal
freedom and encouraging public participation in politics, which are
welcomed by the people.
</P>
<P>
In his address, quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency,
Khatami hailed the people's active participation in the political
scene as one of the greatest achievements of his government since
taking office three years ago.
</P>
<P>
He praised in particular the people's massive turnout in the
sixth parliamentary election in February, which gave his reformist
allies a good opportunity to seize control of the legislative body
long dominated by the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
However, the president, in an implicit way, criticized the
powerful conservatives for their relentless crackdown on the
reformist campaign following the February election, which included
annulment of partial election results, imprisonment of reformist
journalists and the ban of outspoken newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The line between those loyal to the Islamic republic and those
who do not believe in the Islamic republic should be clearly made,
but it does not mean that the opposition to the Islamic republic
should be suppressed, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
"We should not adopt wrong methods in the name of defense of
Islam, the Islamic revolution, leadership and security," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under a direct order of Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, the conservative Guardians Council (GC) finally approved
the election result in Tehran, the political center of the country,
after a three-month-long delay. The move removed the last obstacle
for the new parliament to formally inaugurate on May 27.
</P>
<P>
According to the confirmation by the GC, reformers bagged 26 of
Tehran's 30 seats in the 290-seat parliament. Only two seats went
to conservatives. The other two have to be decided in a re-
competition among four candidates.
</P>
<P>
In other constituencies of the country, reformers also seized
most of the seats, ensuring their dominance in the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservatives still control most of the country's
powerful organs, including the military, judiciary and the
broadcasting network. The political struggle in the country is
destined to intensify further in the future, especially next year
when the presidential election will be held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
