<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Press Welcomes Adoption of Bilateral Accords with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss press has welcomed the
adoption of Switzerland's seven bilateral accords with the
European Union (EU) in Sunday's referendum.
</P>
<P>
Most newspapers Monday hailed the vote as the end of Swiss
isolationism and the start of a normalization of relations with
the EU, according to a Swiss Radio International report.
</P>
<P>
The German-language Neue Zurcher Zeitung said that it is a
clear victory for the government's Europe policy, but warned that
it must not be interpreted as any more than a "yes" to the seven
bilateral accords.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a signal for rapid membership of the EU; nor does it
mean the end of the process of integration with the EU," it added.
</P>
<P>
The Zurich-based Tages Anzeiger said that the scale of the vote
for the accords (67 percent) was a welcome surprise, and that the
result was due to a marriage of political vision and economic
sense, as well as the fact that Switzerland is doing rather well
economically.
</P>
<P>
However, the Tages Anzeiger warned that it would be dangerous
for the government to channel this newly-won political capital
into a head-on campaign for entry into the EU. It said this would
play into the hands of right-wing populists. Instead, the paper
argued, next on the list should be a rethink on Switzerland's
relations with the United Nations and NATO.
</P>
<P>
The main French-language daily, Le Temps, declared that the
language divide was non-existent in the vote, and that the results
surpassed even the most optimistic prognosis. It concluded the age
of pessimism that colored Swiss politics in 1992 has been replaced
by a new-found confidence and ambition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Le Temps said, the issue of EU membership has not
gone away and calls for a major debate. But at least a taboo has
been abolished, it added, so that a debate is now possible.
</P>
<P>
In the Italian-spoken Ticino, where the vote against the
treaties was largest, newspapers called on the federal government
not to ignore its voice even if the result in the rest of
Switzerland was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
They said the region's distrust is a direct result of the
federal government's persistent shortsightedness and refusal to
consider the canton's real fears about pressure on the regional
job market and an avalanche of trucks passing through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
