<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Faces Shortage of 500 Radiologists: Medical Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- With the aging problem increasing,
Canada is facing a shortage of 500 radiologists by 2004, says the
country's medical profession.
</P>
<P>
In its latest warning made available here Monday, both the
Canadian Medical Association and the Canadian Association of
Radiologists say there are far too few radiologists to read the
imaging results from sophisticated machines such as CT scanners
and MRIs.
</P>
<P>
The country is already suffering a shortfall of 150 full-time
radiologists, about eight percent of the medical specialty's total
workforce.
</P>
<P>
Doctors are exhausted, frustrated and stressed, they say,
urging immediate measures ranging from increasing medical school
enrollment to establishing a medical technology fund.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the "looming crisis" to the early '90s decision
by federal and provincial governments to severely limit the number
of practicing physicians.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the health ministers endorsed a plan to reduce
Canadian medical school entry class sizes by 10 percent by the
fall of 1993.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the cuts is now just beginning to be felt as it
takes several years to educate a physician, according to Canadian
doctors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
