<HEADLINE> Annan Dismisses Role for Rebel Leader in Sierra Leone Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday dismissed the role for Sierra Leone rebel leader,
Foday Sankoh, in any peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Annan said, "I think the longer-term
fate of Foday Sankoh is being discussed seriously now."
</P>
<P>
"I believe by his behavior, he has excluded himself from the
process," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"And I don't see how one can consider him part of any peace
process in Sierra Leone," the Secretary-General said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations is determined to bring all
detainees to safety.
</P>
<P>
"We had 54 released yesterday -- 54 additional peacekeepers.
We expect more to be released in the course of this week," he
added.
</P>
<P>
 About 8,700 U.N. peacekeepers arrived in Sierra Leone in
April to monitor a peace accord signed by the Government of Sierra
Leone and the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels in July last
year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 500 U.N. peacekeepers were taken hostage in early
May by the RUF led by Foday, who was arrested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The group released Sunday was composed of 10 Kenyans, 42
Zambians, one Malaysian and one Norwegian. The rebels are still
holding 280 U.N. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. contingent now numbers 10,400, the largest U.N.
peacekeeping deployment in the world, and has been authorized to
grow to 13,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
