<HEADLINE> Annan Calls For Immediate Ceasefire Between Ethiopia, Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday called, in the strongest possible terms, for an
immediate ceasefire between Ethiopia and Eritrea in accordance
with U.N. Security Council resolutions 1297 and 1298 so as to give
peace a chance.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the large scale of
hostilities between Ethiopia and Eritrea has resumed.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by his spokesman's office said the Secretary-
General had been following closely and with increasing concern the
latest developments of the situation.
</P>
<P>
"He has, from the outset two years ago, sought to promote a
peaceful settlement of the border dispute between the two
countries," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is immensely saddened at the resumption
of what is an increasing incomprehensible war. There can be no
justification for such large-scale death and suffering, especially
at a time when both countries are wracked by drought and hunger,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General wishes to take this opportunity to
express his full support for the current mission of Mr. Ahmed
Ouyahia, the Special Envoy of OAU (the Organization of the African
Unity) Chairman and Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika and
for the efforts of other peace envoys. He urged the governments of
Ethiopia and Eritrea to seize this opportunity," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
The bitter border conflict between the two countries erupted in
May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The two sides broke off indirect talks in Algiers on May 4
after Ethiopia accused Eritrea of setting preconditions. Ethiopia
said Eritrea has demanded the two sides sign the three-part, OAU
drafted accord and approve a cease-fire as a prerequisite for any
substantive discussions.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council has imposed arms embargo on
both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
