<HEADLINE> Marc Dutroux Appears in Court Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Marc Dutroux, the alleged child
abuser and killer in Belgium, appeared Monday a second time in
court for breaking loose and running away from police for more
than three hours in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Neufchateau correctional tribunal held a hearing of the
Dutroux runaway case. The Belgian court is yet to start trial of
Dutroux for allegedly abusing little girls and voluntarily killing
four of the six girls forcefully kept on his premises.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux, the most notorious prisoner in the country, broke away
from two escorting policemen prior to a court hearing at
Neufchateau on March 23, 1998. He ran away with one of the
handguns of the policemen and snatched a motor vehicle from a
passer-by just outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
The man remained at large for more than three and a half hours
before being caught again by a forest policeman some 15 kilometers
away from the court at Neufchateau. Thousands of policemen from
Belgium, Luxembourg, France and Germany were mobilized to join the
manhunt.
</P>
<P>
A verdict is expected to be emitted by the court on June 19.
</P>
<P>
The runaway incident shocked the nation and caused two Belgian
cabinet members to resign.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux has been detained for four years by now, waiting for
court trial for what he was accused of. Trials will not be held
before 2001.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested in August 1996 on charges of raping, torturing
and assassinating four little girls, of whom two died from
starvation on his premises after he was arrested by the police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
