<HEADLINE> Egypt, Morocco Sign Protocol on Enhancing Development, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Morocco on Monday signed
here a protocol on the establishment of an association aimed at
promoting development and investment in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was signed by Mahmoud al Arabi, chairman of the
Egyptian Federation of Chambers of Commerce, and his Moroccan
counterpart Abdallah Zoheir, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The protocol encourages reciprocal investment and partnership
between the two countries and calls for promotion of trade exchange
and technology transfer, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
It is aimed at strengthening economic, social and trade
cooperation between the two countries, cementing ties of friendship
and activating the partnership agreement in quest of a
comprehensive and sustainable development in the interests of the
two countries, it added.
</P>
<P>
It urges investors and businessmen in both countries to draw up
mechanisms that enable them to get acquainted with each other's
investment chances.
</P>
<P>
Al Arabi and Zoheir spoke highly of the development of the
bilateral relations as a result of continued direct contact between
the two countries' top officials in the economic sector.
</P>
<P>
They called on chambers of commerce in both countries to do
their utmost to effect a surge in the Egyptian-Moroccan relations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Morocco increased their trade volume by 85 percent to
37 million U.S. dollars in 1999 from 20 million dollars in 1996.
They hope to enhance the volume to an annual 100 million dollars in
light of the free trade agreement signed in April, 1999. They also
have a vision to raise the trade volume to one billion dollars in
2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
