<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Bans Weekly for Censorship Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan authorities Monday
banned the printing and publication of an English-language weekly
for violating the government's censorship laws, the state radio
said.
</P>
<P>
The weekly, The Sunday Leader, was the second paper to be
closed down in less than a week amid fighting between government
troops and separatist Tamil Tiger rebels in the northern Jaffna
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted the government censor as saying the newspaper
reported on the war in a way that "would have benefited the enemy.
"
</P>
<P>
The radio said The Sunday Leader and other publications of the
Leader Publications (Pvt. Ltd. had been shut down for six months
after several warnings to obey the censorship laws.
</P>
<P>
The tough new censorship laws came into force for both the
local and foreign media earlier this month as fighting escalated
between government troops and the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
rebels who are engaged in ferocious assaults in a bid to retake
their former stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday the government temporarily closed down the Tamil-
language Uthayan newspaper in Jaffna for violating the censorship
laws.
</P>
<P>
Local and international media groups have urged the government
to ease restrictions imposed on both local and foreign
correspondents based in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Lakshman Kiriella
promised Sunday that press censorship in the island nation would
be lifted soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
