<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Postpone Flag Meeting on Enclave Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- India's Border Security Force (BSF)
Sunday night postponed a proposed flag meeting with Bangladesh
Rifles(BDR) to settle a conflict in a Bangladeshi enclave within
India, the official Bangladesh News Agency announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
BDR has so far sent 10 official letters, including protest
letters, inviting BSF to sit for a dialogue in a flag meeting to
solve the problem at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred Indians, allegedly supported by BSF personnel,
Thursday intruded the Bangladeshi enclave of Mashaldanga under the
district of Kurigram, about 400 kilometers northwest of Dhaka, and
abducted Bangladesh nationals, set ablaze around 55 houses and
looted valuables and cattle. The Bangladesh nationals were,
however, released later.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 women and children reportedly received injuries
during the attack that lasted at least one hour.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the enclave is reported to be in acute shortage of
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its more than 2,
000 inhabitants, who are now virtually confined in the Indian
territory since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A district official was quoted as saying it is difficult to
provide relief materials even to the people of the enclave as it
is 1.5 kilometers from the mainland. The confined people are
surrounded,guarded and restricted by Indian BSF and police from
coming to the mainland of Bangladesh, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
