<HEADLINE> 70 LTTE Rebels Killed in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 70 Tamil rebels were
killed in a face-to-face battle with government troops who used
aircraft and artillery to repulse fresh assaults by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) in Sri Lanka's Jaffna peninsula, the
Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Colombo, the Sri Lankan
capital, Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan Army claimed to have successfully repulsed two
more attempts by "well-armed guerrillas" to break through the
defenses on the outskirts of Chavakachechri, a small but strategic
town which the rebels claim they captured from the army Saturday
evening, the PTI reported.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were killed in fierce fighting with the troops at
Sirasali, about five kilometers east of Chavakachechri, the PTI
quoted a Sri Lankan government spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the LTTE suffered such a major
loss since it launched its new offensive to recapture Jaffna on
May 10, the PTI said.
</P>
<P>
The PTI also reported from Colombo that the Sri Lankan
government Monday said it had decided to explore "diplomatic means
" to invite India to join the mediation process toward a
negotiated solution of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the PTI, India's Cabinet Committee on
Security Monday held a meeting to discuss the situation in Sri
Lanka. Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee chaired the
meeting, which was attended by senior officials including Defense
Minister George Fernandes and the chiefs of the three service of
the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Indian National Security Advisor Brajesh Mishra and
the three service chiefs of the armed forces reviewed the latest
developments in the situation in the Jaffna peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
