<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Seize 187 Kilograms of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish anti-narcotics police on
Monday seized 187 kilograms of heroin in Bagcilar district of
Istanbul, the biggest city of the country.
</P>
<P>
Acting on a tip-off, the police conducted an operation in the
district, and seized the drugs with a market price of nearly two
trillion Turkish Liras (four million U.S. dollars) in a house, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Three suspects were taken into custody in the operation. They
confessed that the drugs were brought in from Iran, and would be
marketed in Britain.
</P>
<P>
During the operation, the police also confiscated two automatic
weapons, 10,000 German marks (about 4,595 dollars), and two
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
In the last five months, the police have seized a total of 1.2
tons of heroin, 103 kilograms of hashish, 1.2 kilograms of cocaine,
15 kilograms of opium, 4.4 litres of acid anhydride, one of the raw
materials to be used in abstracting heroin, and 309,892 drug pills.
Also 757 people were arrested in the campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Journalists Condemn Government's Decision to Suspend Opposition Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Journalists Union on
Monday condemned the government's decision to suspend the
publication of the mouthpiece of an opposition party, saying the
move was against the country's constitution and press law.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for Parties' Affairs, which is made up of
officials and those close to the government, suspended on Saturday
the opposition Labor Party and its mouthpiece, Al-Shaab newspaper,
until the party resolves an internal power struggle.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaab has been accused by government press of inciting
violent demonstrations by Al-Azhar University students against the
allegedly blasphemous novel, "Feast of the Seaweeds," written by
Syrian writer Haidar Haidar.
</P>
<P>
"The board of the Egyptian Journalists Union denounces the
decision to suspend the party and the paper, and believes it is a
blow to public freedom," the union said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Al-Shaab's suspension is contrary to articles 48 and 208 of the
Egyptian constitution and article five of the law on the press,
which forbids the suspension or closure of newspapers by
administrative decisions," it said.
</P>
<P>
The union leadership "urges all political and union bodies and
non-governmental organizations to use legal means to block the
decision which undermines liberty of expression," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty Al-Shaab journalists launched a sit-in on Sunday at the
headquarters of the journalists union in downtown Cairo to protest
the suspension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge to Year's Low in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plunged to this year
's low on Singapore Stock Market Monday as U.S. NASDAQ's 4-percent
drop on Friday and U.S. Federal Reserve's tough stance on
inflation dampened market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) dropped 62.54 points to
end at 1,929.88 in light trading.
</P>
<P>
The market volume totaled 234 million shares worth 524.96
million Singapore dollars (303.92 million U.S. dollars). Declining
issues overwhelmed advancers by 284 to 54 with 203 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was a 12.52 million parcel by SingTel which
was transacted at 2.23 Singapore dollars per share. It was
followed by NatElec which had 11.21 million units done. Chew
EuHock was the next with 10.39 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Bukit Sem led the ascent of the day climbing up 40 cents to
close at 13.4 Singapore dollars. SembLog edged up 30 cents to
finish at 10.4 Singapore dollars. Datacrft inched up 15 cents to
end at 7.75 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 was the biggest loser of the day, plummeting 300
cents to close at 44.1 Singapore dollars. SPH sank 160 cents to
finish at 27.6 Singapore dollars. SPH tumbled by 150 cents to end
at 27.6 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed Monday's sharp drop in share prices to the
bearish sentiment following NASDAQ's big losses on Friday and U.S.
Federal Reserve's signal that it would not go soft on curbing
inflation.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that electronic stocks suffered the heaviest
losses and banking stocks also fared poorly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
