<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Forces Counterattack in Northern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's northern alliance
forces Monday launched a major counter-offensive against the
ruling Taliban militia, the Afghan Islamic Press(AIP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The counter-offensive was aimed at recapturing the territory
they lost to the Islamic militia in the Hindukush range of
Afghanistan over the weekend, said the Pakistan-based agency.
</P>
<P>
According to initial reports, six soldiers were killed and
eight wounded from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Heavy artillery and tanks were being used by both sides in the
fierce fighting in the Salang area of Baghlan Province,said AIP.
</P>
<P>
The two factions have been fighting each other for the past
several years. After the winter's short peace, fighting erupted
again this year following the advent of summer in northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
AIP said the Taliban controlled the Salang-Baghlan highway
while the fighters loyal to opposition commander Ahmad Shah Masood
had occupied the heights of Hindukush overlooking the highway.
</P>
<P>
The Hindukush range separates northern Afghanistan while the
Salang tunnel is the sole major highway connection between the two
parts.
</P>
<P>
Masood's forces fortified themselves in the mountainous
Panjsher Valley while the Taliban control the rest of the country.
If the Taliban forces could seize the Salang area,they could
threaten Andarab, a strategic center of the Masood forces, AIP
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
