<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Appoints Chief Election Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi President Shahabuddin
Ahmed appointed M. A. Sayeed, a former civil servant, as the
country's new chief election commissioner (CEC) Monday, after the
post had been left vacant for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Nominated by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina under Articles 118
and 48 of the Bangladesh Constitution, Sayeed became the eighth
CEC of the country after the resignation of Mohammad Abu Hena on
May 8 for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
Sayeed, as the second civil servant to hold this constitutional
post in independent Bangladesh, held several important government
positions before, such as secretary of agriculture, secretary of
home affairs and secretary of information.
</P>
<P>
Press secretary to the prime minister Jawadul Karim described
Sayeed as a "senior, honest and dedicated officer" while briefing
reporters on the appointment.
</P>
<P>
After the resignation of Hena on May 8, Prime Minister Hasina
wrote a letter to the leader of the opposition, Khaleda Zia,
inviting her for discussions on the appointment of a new CEC.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition showed no interest in sitting with the
government to reach a consensus on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The ruling and the opposition parties had made accusations and
counter-accusations against each other in finding the right person
to fill up the important post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
