<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Poses as Regional Powerhouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa accounts for
almost three- quarters of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC)'s economic output with only a quarter of its
population.
</P>
<P>
But it ranks third behind two Indian Ocean island states of
Seychelles and Mauritius as far as per capita income is concerned.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by international economics consultancy WEFA
Southern Africa, Seychelles had an annual per capita income of
7,145 U.S. dollars in 1997, which more than doubled South
Africa's figure of 3,454 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius had a per capita income of 3,827 dollars, 11 percent
higher than that of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the other end of the economic spectrum, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), while accounting for more than 28
percent of the total SADC population, contributes just over 3
percent to its total economic output. The DRC had a per capita
income of just 127 dollars, and Mozambique was marginally higher
at 140 dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to WEFA, the two poorest SADC countries showed
remarkably different economic fortunes during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"Mozambique reaped its peace dividend and enjoyed an average
annual economic growth rate of 6.2 percent between 1990 and 1997,
while the deepening of the DRC civil war resulted in its economy
declining at an average rate of minus 6.1 percent per annum over
the same period," the consultancy said.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican economy grew faster than any other SADC member
state between 1990 and 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Economy Up 0.9% in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The South African economy grew
by 0.9 percent in the first quarter of this year, Statistics South
Africa announced in Pretoria on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency's director Mark Orkin said this was the lowest
quarterly increase in the seasonally adjusted real gross domestic
product (GDP) at market prices since the 0.6 percent recorded in
the last three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The main countervailing factors -- off-setting growth or
relative stability in other industries -- was the sharp drop in
agriculture, forestry and fishing due to high rainfalls and
floods," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The 0.9 percent rise in the first quarter of this year was,
nevertheless, the sixth quarterly increase in a row.
</P>
<P>
This was mainly because of increasing activity in three
industries -- hotels and restaurants (which grew by 0.5 percent),
real estate and business services (0.5 percent) and transport and
communication (0.4 percent).
</P>
<P>
An annual growth rate of 1.2 percent was recorded last year
following a fourth quarter jump of 3.6 percent in the GDP.
</P>
<P>
This compared to an annual growth rate of 0.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The GDP in the first three quarters of last year were 1.1
percent, 2.1 percent and 3.2 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
