<HEADLINE> S. Africa Minister Says Not to Close Higher Education Institutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- South African Education
Minister Kader Asmal on Monday dismissed as unfounded fears that a
review of the higher education system was aimed at closure of
some institutions.
</P>
<P>
He said his intention was not to close institutions such as
historically disadvantaged universities and technikons
experiencing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, the reconfiguration exercise is key to
preventing closure of those institutions that are in crisis,"
Asmal said in a statement issued in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Soon after taking office in July last year, Asmal said the
shape and size of higher education could not be left to chance and
should be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated last Wednesday that the exercise was
likely to result in mergers between some institutions, and
decisions to change the missions of others. 
</P>
