<HEADLINE> France Urges Syria to Help Ease Situation in Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac on
Monday urged Syria to help ease tension in southern Lebanon while
Israel is pulling out its troops from there and leaving behind a
vacuum of power.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Syrian President Hafez Assad,
Chirac said he is worried about the present situation in southern
Lebanon and hopes all countries in the region will cooperate in
easing the tension.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also called for an immediate session of the Monitoring
Committee of the Truce in Southern Lebanon, which consists of
France, the United States, Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up in 1996 to supervise an agreement
between Israel and the Syria-backed Hezbollah guerrillas on
avoiding striking civilian targets in their tit-for-tat attacks
against each other.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the committee was suspended in January after
Israel pulled out of the talks of the committee in protest against
the death of an Israeli soldier in a Hezbollah attack.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak ordered
the Israeli army to be ready to end its 22-year occupation of
southern Lebanon as early as June 1 -- five weeks ahead of his own
July 7 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council is due to decide whether
the 4,500-member U.N peacekeeping force in Lebanon, established
from nine countries in 1978, will be expanded to deploy in the
areas evacuated by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel established a buffer zone in southern Lebanon to block
attacks on northern Israeli towns. It hoped to withdraw as part
of a broad peace deal with Syria, the main power in Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
