<HEADLINE> 2300-Year-Old Tomb Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- An ancient tomb, which dates back
to the Warring States Period (475-221 BCE) has been unearthed in
the northern part of the north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
This is first Warring States tomb discovered in this part of
Shanxi Province, said archeologists, adding that the tomb will
provide rare and invaluable materials for research into the
culture and history of the Warring States Period.
</P>
<P>
The tomb may belong to a noble family. Three chambers have been
discovered in the tomb, according to the archeologists.
</P>
<P>
One of the chambers has been unearthed along with more than 100
items of pottery, jade ware, and copper.  
</P>
