<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plants Trees with WB Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China has planted 75,000 hectares of
fast-growing trees in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province with
the loan from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The 17.64-million-U.S.-dollar WB loan was the largest ever
granted to China for afforestation. The trees to be planted in the
relatively cold northeast will be mature in 25 years, instead of
the usual 35 years.
</P>
<P>
The forest is expected to yield some nine million cubic meters
of timber with an output value of 3.9 billion yuan (470 million U.
S. dollars) in the future.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Province, one of the key forest zones in China,
started cooperation with the World Bank in 1985.  
</P>
</TEXT>
