<HEADLINE> Australia Supports China's WTO Membership (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian Minister for Trade Mark
Vaile said here today he believes that China's entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO) will benefit other members of the
global trading system, including Australia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He told a news conference that momentum for China's accession
to the WTO is continuing, and all parties concerned should spur on
the momentum, not only for China's membership in the WTO, but also
for launching a new round of WTO negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Vaile, who is leading an Australian business delegation
comprised of 74 senior business representatives covering a range
of areas, and Chinese Foreign Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng
formally signed an agreement on China's entry into the WTO earlier
today.
</P>
<P>
He said that his China visit came at a critical stage in China'
s entry into the WTO: China and the European Union just concluded
their talks on China's WTO entry, and the U.S. congress is going
to vote on granting Permanent Normal Trade Relations (PNTR) status
for China.
