<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Humanization Key to Digital Gap (2)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics also show that Asia has roughly three-fifths of the
world's population, but only one in five of the world's Internet
users is from there. South Asia is home to one-fifth of the world'
s population, but only 1 percent of its people use the Internet,
while the United States, with 5 percent of the world's population,
accounts for more than half of the world's Internet users.
</P>
<P>
This disparity is more troubling when one considers the fact
that four out of five people in the world have never used a
telephone, let alone sent an e-mail, Bradley said. And even if the
rest of the world were connected, they would need to learn English,
since four out of five sites on the web are in English, a language
that is understood by only one-tenth of the world's population, he
added.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Bradley noted, technology has to be simple to use,
certainly simpler than it is now, with hardware connecting
seamlessly, without conflicting with other devices, and software
loading easily and functioning properly.
</P>
<P>
Making it accessible means putting all the pieces of technology
together and making them easily available to customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, making it personal is more than loading a web page
with an individually tailored selection of news, sports, stock
quotes and weather, the Gateway vice-president explained. It must
also ensure that people know how to use the technology they have
purchased.
</P>
<P>
"Bridging the divide isn't just about selling more personal
computers and Internet service," Bradley said. "It's about such
fundamental issues as productivity and efficiency and global
competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
Digital revolution depends upon having trained workers to
extend its horizon and consumers eager to enjoy its benefits, he
added. Companies should take bridging the division as a particular
responsibility, including teaching computing skills to teachers,
students and the public.
</P>
<P>
"All of us have a vested stake in our digital future whether we
are computer makers or software developers, or simply customers,"
Bradley concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Humanization Key to Bridging Digital Gap (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Humanization of the digital
revolution is, perhaps, the only way out for bridging the
increasingly-widened digital gap around the world today, analysts
here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Internet Industry Analysts believe that the cost that will be
paid for the digital revolution is alienation of a different form
as millions and millions of people are in the process of getting
left at the station as technology's bullet train hurtles ahead.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the Third Annual Business Week Digital Economy
Forum, being held here from May 22 to 24, agreed that the
effective way to narrow the gap brought up by the digital
revolution is humanizing it.
</P>
<P>
"What humanizing the digital revolution really boils down is to
make it more simple, accessible and personal," said Todd Bradley,
executive vice-president of global operation of the U.S.-based
Gateway Inc. Humanization means connecting folks gingerly into a
world of unparalleled technological opportunity, he added.
</P>
<P>
Bradley stressed that businesses responsible for taking
technology forward need to be at the forefront of a movement to
bridge the digital divide opening up between the technology haves
and have-nots to avoid profound social alienation.
</P>
<P>
The analysts cautioned that as rapid development in the
technology field is profoundly changing the way people live, learn,
work and play in the 21st century, the digital division between
the rich and the poor and that between the west and east are
getting wider and wider.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, twice as many classrooms in affluent
districts are connected to the Internet as they are in poorer ones,
African-Americans and Hispanics are 40 percent less likely to have
Internet access than whites, urbanites are 50 percent more likely
to have Internet access than rural residents, and those earning
more than 75,000 dollars a year are 20 times more likely to have
Internet access that those who make less, according to Bradley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
