<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Minister Leaves for Refugee Talks in Bhutan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Foreign Minister Chakra
Bastola left here for Thimpu, Bhutan, Monday for the 9th
ministerial-level talks on the Bhutanese refugee issue to be held
from May 22 to 25.
</P>
<P>
Bastola told reporters at the airport before his departure that
the Bhutanese government are becoming "more positive in solving
the refugee issue."
</P>
<P>
"The Bhutanese government should be committed politically to
solving the refugee crisis," said Bastola.
</P>
<P>
The 9th round of Nepal-Bhutan Joint Ministerial Level Committee
Meeting (JMLC) will focus on the modality for verifying the
refugees, according to the Nepalese Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are living in eastern Nepal
and they are divided into four categories: bona fide Bhutanese who
were forcibly evicted, Bhutanese who emigrated under compelling
circumstances,non-Bhutanese and Bhutanese with criminal records.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the verification will lead to the
repatriation of those who are genuine Bhutanese.
</P>
<P>
The previous JMLC meeting was concluded in Kathmandu in
September last year with Bhutan agreeing to go ahead with field
verification for the first time. However, the talks were
inconclusive as the two sides could not agree on the modality of
the verification process.
</P>
<P>
The eight rounds of ministerial talks between the two Himalayan
kingdoms have so far failed to reach any agreement on the
repatriation of the refugees who left Bhutan in early 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
