<HEADLINE> Lesotho Government Tables Vehicle Theft Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government on
Monday introduced legislation aimed at curbing the rising
cross-border car theft, the South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the second reading of the Motor Vehicle Theft Bill,
Home Affairs Minister Mopshatla Mabitle said the main purpose of
the legislation was to "address the escalating theft of motor
vehicles and motor vehicle parts between Lesotho and South
Africa."
</P>
<P>
He said stolen vehicles were piling up at police stations in
Lesotho. The suspects were often released on bail and most fled to
South Africa where it was difficult to trace them.
</P>
<P>
He said the bill provided for heavy penalties for tampering
with motor vehicles, using false identification plates, breaking
into motor vehicles and dealing in stolen vehicles.
</P>
<P>
It also covered the unlawful disposal of vehicles without
proper documents.
</P>
<P>
A numbers of participants in the debate stressed the need for
stringent measures to curb cross-border car theft, and one
proposed that car thieves should have a leg and arm amputated "to
underline the seriousness of the crime". 
</P>
</TEXT>
