<HEADLINE> Vietnam Expects Improvement of Relations With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam hopes to further develop
relations with France in the economic and cultural fields,
visiting Vietnamese Communist Party Chief Le Kha Phieu said on
Monday when he met with French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Chirac met the General Secretary of the Vietnamese Communist
Party at the Elysee presidential palace. He said that France
fully backs Vietnam's policy of reform and opening up, according
to presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also praised the reinforcement of relations between
Paris and Hanoi since his visit to Vietnam in 1997, and hoped that
the visit by Phieu will bring a new vitality to bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
France, Vietnam's second largest donor country following Japan,
has 28 major economic and cultural cooperative projects in Vietnam
while about 100 French companies invested in the country.
</P>
<P>
Le Kha Phieu said that despite colonial relations in history,
Vietnam and France are seeking mutual understanding and sincere
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Vietnam supports France's stand on
globalization and welcomes its policy to support developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Phieu, the first Vietnamese Communist Party chief to visit
France, is accompanied by a large delegation. Vice-Prime Minister
Nguyen Tan Dung, Foreign Minister Nguyen Dy Nien, Minister of
Health Do Nguyen Phuong, Minister of Transport Le Ngoc Hoan, and
35 heads of state-owned and private enterprises are among the
members of the 100-man delegation.
</P>
<P>
Phieu will meet with French Senate President Christian Poncelet
and National Assembly President Raymond Forni on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He will also attend the signing of a bilateral agreement on
maritime transport and will meet with the Chamber of Commerce and
Industry of Paris during his four-day visit in France.
</P>
<P>
He will travel to an agricultural city in Poitiers, central
France, and visit the European aeronautics constructor Airbus
consortium in Toulouse, southwest France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
