<HEADLINE> Philippine Leader Rules Out State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Monday that the government will not declare a state of
emergency despite some bombing incidents in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the presidential palace,
Estrada said he condemned the bombing of SM Megamall Sunday which
killed one person and injured several others as well as the
bombing of Glorietta Mall in Makati City last week.
</P>
<P>
These bombings, the president said, were acts of cowardice
committed by terrorists whose agenda is to sow fear among the
people and destabilize the government.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said his government can solve the problem without
declaring a state of emergency. "I have enough powers under the
constitution to smash terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government is not helpless in fighting
terrorism. "Let me be clear. We are not helpless in this fight. We
can and will insure the safety and security of all Filipinos
throughout the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the intelligence services of the Armed Forces of
the Philippines (AFP) and the Philippine National Police (PNP) are
now stepping up their operations to ferret out these terrorists "
at the soonest possible time."
</P>
<P>
According to the president, while the PNP has intensified its
investigation into the bombing incidents, he has at the same time
ordered the Department of Interior and Local Government to
mobilize local government units to help prevent acts of terrorism
in their respective localities.
</P>
<P>
"Local executives should seek the assistance of private and
public establishments in their areas to adopt more effective
security measures to protect the public against these acts," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada asked the people to be more vigilant and be
more security conscious, calling on them to cooperate with the law
enforcement agencies that will be implementing measures for their
safety.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the people to go on and live their normal lives."
This would be our best response to those forces who want to
confuse and terrorize us and derail our national progress and
development," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
