<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Economies Recover, Risks Remain: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Asia-Pacific economies can look
forward to optimistic growth prospects in the immediate future,
but should realize downside risks, the United Nations said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the launch of its annual Economic and Social Survey of Asia
and the Pacific, the U.N. Economic and Social Commission for Asia
and the Pacific (ESCAP) said the recovery from the crisis, which
happened almost three years ago, has been "broad-based."
</P>
<P>
All the subregions, except South and Southwest Asia, have shown
improved growth performance.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the recovery to fiscal stimulus policy
practiced in many regional economies and better export performance,
saying the combination of the two factors helped increase capacity
utilization and contained a rise in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"The current indications suggest reasonably optimistic
prospects for the further strengthening of regional growth in the
immediate future," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The agency forecast a 6.2-percent gross domestic product growth
rate for the regional developing economies in 2000, 0.6 percent
higher than the rate achieved in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing progress in financial restructuring, the potential
for further easing of the monetary policy stance and falling
interest rates and the likelihood of maintaining a strong export
performance, easing of the credit crunch and higher global demand
were all cited as the elements underlying the optimistic
projection.
</P>
<P>
The report also expected further progress in corporate debt
restructuring, stable exchange rates, strong export performance
and return of private capital inflows into the region to help
sustain the recovery.
</P>
<P>
Despite the optimistic scenario, however, the U.N. agency
warned that the region is not free from some downside risks which
pose a number of policy challenges.
</P>
<P>
The much-needed structural reforms may generate a sense of
uncertainty with respect to employment prospects and thus dampen
the pickup in domestic demand, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the plagued financial sectors in many regional
economies, over-reliance on external demand, comparatively low
agricultural productivity, limitation of fiscal stimulus policy
and an uncertain external environment can also dampen the momentum
of recovery, noted the report.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP also urged developing economies in the region to
establish and strengthen social security and safety nets, saying
the issues have become "prominent of late, especially after the
crisis."
</P>
<P>
A number of formal social security and safety arrangements are
currently in operation or under consideration within the region to
provide protection against involuntary unemployment or loss of
income due to ill health and old age.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, the coverage remains highly limited,
suggesting the establishment of new programs, greater reliance on
market-based or other non-governmental programs and reforms in
existing programs.
</P>
<P>
The report also urged efforts to improve economic and financial
monitoring and surveillance in the region, saying that this is "an
integral part of the overall response" to the call for the
international financial system reform after the Asian crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Expects 6.4-Pct GDP Growth in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is expected to reach the
official projection of a 6.4-precent gross domestic product growth
rate in fiscal year 1999-2000, following a significant increase in
crop production and industrial and service sector output,
according to a survey released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"A bumper harvest of rice crop, an upturn in industrial
production and a higher output in the construction, power,
transport and wholesale and retail trade would help achieve the
growth target," Director General of Bangladesh Institute of
Development Studies Abu Ahmed Abdullah said when formally
launching the "Economic and Social Survey for Asia and the Pacific
2000."
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Bangladesh has maintained a steady growth in
comparison with other South Asian countries despite devastating
floods in 1998 which lowered projections.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate rose to nearly 9 percent in 1999
from 7 percent in the previous year due to a flood-related decline
in food and industrial production, Abdullah said, adding that both
food and non-food prices dropped at the end of 1999 as direct
effects of the floods eased.
</P>
<P>
Referring to trade and exchange rates, he said export growth
declined to less than 3 percent in 1999 from nearly 17 percent
recorded in the previous year, as extensive flooding depressed
production and disrupted transport and communication links.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, import payments rose by 7 percent as
expenditure on foodgrain imports rose significantly in response to
a flood-related shortfall in domestic supplies.
</P>
<P>
Import liberalization, removal of import restrictions and
reduction in import duties have made Bangladesh a more outward-
looking trade regime, said Abdullah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
