<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Hails Swiss Vote on EU Treaties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- President of the European
Commission Romano Prodi on Monday welcomed the result of the Swiss
referendum on the country's economic treaties with the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Prodi said in a written statement that the result of the
referendum has clearly demonstrated the will of the Swiss people
to further develop and foster relations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
"It is a milestone on our joint road toward prosperity and
stability in Europe, to the benefit of the people of Switzerland
and of the European Union," said Prodi.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland held a national referendum on Sunday on seven
bilateral economic agreements with the 15-nation bloc and more
than two thirds of the voters voted in favor of the agreements.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said the Swiss-EU agreements will further improve the
already excellent good-neighborly relations between the two sides
with many positive effects on the daily life of the citizens in
these countries.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements shall bring about considerable strengthening of
our relations, but in no way pre-judge any steps to further
integration," said the president of the commission, the executive
body of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament, the legislative body of the EU, has
already approved the agreements concerning transit transport, free
movement of people and bilateral trade and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The parliaments of our member states will have to give their
approval to the agreement on the free movement of persons. The
matter will be treated as a priority, and I am confident that the
agreement can start to apply sometime in 2001," said Prodi.
</P>
</TEXT>
