<HEADLINE> France Considers U.N. Mission in Southern Lebanon Dangerous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain Richard
said on Monday that a planned U.N. peacekeeping operation in
southern Lebanon will be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg, Richard said
that the feasiblity of a participation by France in such a mission
will be assessed with "maximum precautions."
</P>
<P>
He warned that U.N. peacekeepers could be attacked on several
fronts by "extremely violent people" and the international
community will be "discredited" if such the mission fails to push
forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is expected to submit on
Tuesday to the Security Council a report on the role of the United
Nations in southern Lebanon after Israel pulls out its troops from
there.
</P>
<P>
Annan is likely to suggest a re-deployment of a 4,500-member U.
N. peacekeeping force, established by nine countries in 1978 and
including 250 soldiers from France, in the areas of Lebanon
evacuated by Israel in the coming weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
