<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet GDP Up 9.6 Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product (GDP) of
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region reached a record of 10
billion yuan (about 1.25 billion U.S.dollars) in 1999, up 9.6
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released during the third session of the
Seventh Tibet Autonomous Regional People's Congress, which opened
in Lhasa today, growth in the local economy last year was due to
the steady development in farming and pasturing.
</P>
<P>
The grain output in Tibet reported 922,000 tons in 1999.
Meanwhile, the region's industrial volume reached 998 million yuan,
up 6.4 percent over 1998.
</P>
<P>
The service industry has become a major driving force in the
region's economy. Last year the sector topped 1.74 billion yuan,
up 10.2 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Tibet received a total of 448,000 domestic and
overseas tourists and earned 36.3 million U.S. dollars in tourism,
up 9.9 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Tibet invested 5.66 billion yuan in dozens of
construction projects, including infrastructure, power, water-
conservancy and transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
