<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Up in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Dropping prices and holidays helped
drive the volume of retail sales by 9.1 percent in April, official
figures show.
</P>
<P>
According to figures that the National Bureau of Statistics (
NBS) released today, retail sales surged by 9.1 percent over one
year ago to 257.15 billion yuan (about 31 billion US dollars) in
April.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales for the first four months totaled 1.1 trillion
yuan, 10.1 percent more than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
NBS said this is an indication that the consumption market
continues to improve, though slowly.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, earlier figures showed that consumer price
index (CPI), a crucial indicator of the consumption demand,
dropped by nearly one percent over the previous month in April.
</P>
<P>
NBS said that discount on clothes and price wars among electric
household appliance producers helped drive up sales by 20-53
percent. Sales of air conditioners in Beijing doubled in April.
Sales of cars were also up.
</P>
<P>
Long public holidays around May 1 also helped boost sales of
cameras and other tourist goods.
</P>
<P>
In April, the catering sector saw a growth of sales of 17.9
percent over one year ago. Sales in the trading grew to 11.8
percent while manufacturing sector saw a 4.3 percent increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
