<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But selling across the broader market was modest compared to
other markets in the region, with some counters benefiting from
Friday's announcement that China and the European Union had
reached a deal on China's entry into the World Trade Organization
(WTO).
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index lost 337.53 points or 2.33
percent to close at 14,140.73, recovering somewhat after plunging
416.8 points to close the morning session at 14,061.46.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 10.222 billion HK dollars (1.31 billion U.S.
dollars), compared with Friday's 14.586 billion HK dollars (1.87
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indices of Hang Seng Index, Finance, Properties
and Commerce and Industry suffered a loss of 0.92 percent, 1.99
percent and 3.50 percent, respectively, while Utilities gained 1.
04 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index closed down 2.46 percent
and the Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corp Index down 2.94 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index and the Hang Seng IT Portfolio Index
lost 104 points and 124 points to end at 2,554.46 and 3,400.14,
respectively. 
