<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Protests Turkish Arrest of Iranian Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry on Monday
summoned Turkish ambassador Turan Moraly once again to protest the
arrest of hundreds of Iranian citizens in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Terming the Turkish move as "inhuman," the ministry's Director
General Mohammad Sharif Mahdavi said that the arrest of hundreds of
Iranians by Turkish police aroused grave concern of Iranian
officials and public opinion.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Republic of Iran condemned such inhuman actions of
the Turkish government and urged Ankara to stop such moves and
release the arrested Iranians as soon as possible," he said, quoted
by the official Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Mahdavi also warned that Turkish government should shoulder
responsibility for the consequence of the arrests.
</P>
<P>
Moraly in reply expressed regret over the arrest of Iranians in
Turkey and promised to convey Iran's protest to the Ankara
government as soon as possible to follow up the case.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the Turkish police and security forces stormed
the residences of Iranians in Turkey's largest city Istanbul on
Saturday, rounding up over 300 Iranians amid an intensified
crackdown on Islamic activists.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi on Monday
called the Turkish move "unacceptable" and said "we not only
consider this a despicable move out of context with diplomatic
norms and international regulations, but also an affront to the
good neighborly relations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
He said that due to the emphatic follow-up of Iranian
government, many of the arrested Iranians have been released and
his ministry is continuing a probe into the status of the other
detainees.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry will employ all within its capacity to
stop the measure, Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the ministry had summoned the Turkish envoy to voice
Tehran's "strong dissatisfaction over the expanded anti-Iran
propaganda" by the Turkish mass media.
</P>
<P>
Following the arrest of nine Turkish Islamic activists, Turkish
press accused Iran of being involved in the bomb explosions of two
Turkish journalists in 1993 and 1999. Tehran rejected the
allegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 Israeli Solider Injured in Hezbollah Attacks on Shebaa Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 22 (Xinhua) -- One Israeli solider was injured
Monday morning in Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas attacks on Israeli
positions in the controversial Shebaa Farms, Lebanon's Oriental
radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah fired missiles and mortars at Israeli positions
following a speech made by Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah on
Sunday, which said the resistance will not cease attacks on the
farms after Israel's scheduled withdrawal if the farms are not
included in the withdrawal list.
</P>
<P>
Monday morning, Hezbollah also shelled an Israeli early-warning
station in the Shebaa Farms region located at an altitude of 2,000
meters on Mount Hermon, which can oversee the activities of the
whole Lebanon, Syria, Jordan and some part of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah attacked Israeli positions in Shebaa Farms on Sunday
for the first time since 1989 when the guerrillas killed four
Israeli officers in Jabal Lus in the region.
</P>
<P>
The fertile Shebaa Farms are located on the Lebanese side of
Mount Hermon, now under Israeli occupation. Israel said the farms
belong to Syria, and that a withdrawal from the area would be
considered in its peace talks with Damascus.
</P>
<P>
According to a British-French agreement on the Lebanese-
Palestinian border in 1923, the Shebaa Farms were not included in
the Lebanon side. But Lebanon claimed that the area was bequeathed
to Beirut in an agreement between Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic newspaper Al Hayat reported Sunday that Syria has
informed the United Nations that Lebanon has the ownership of the
Shebaa Farms while Syria enjoys the sovereignty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Indonesian President Undergoes Questioning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Attorney General Office
(AGO on Monday once again examined former president Soeharto at
his residence to get more information on his alleged involvement
in corruption practices.
</P>
<P>
A member of Soeharto's lawyer team, Danny Kailimang, told
Xinhua after the investigation that in the course of the
questioning Soeharto replied as many as 11 questions from
prosecutors. "And he has answered all the questions but in a
simple way," Kailimang said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
He added that the questioning was ceased because the state of
health of the 78-years-old man worsened.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, based on advice of Soeharto's doctors and medical team
from the AGO, the investigation into Pak Harto (Soeharto) was
ceased. The blood pressure of Soeharto arise (due to today's
questioning)," Kailimang said, but hoping the investigation could
be continued next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Spokesman of the AGO Yushar Yahya told Xinhua that
his side has yet to receive a report from the prosecutors on the
result of today's questioning.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that prosecutors have found "leads that
Soeharto committed corruption practices during his rule."
</P>
<P>
"And we will carry on the investigation, so that it could be
completed before the period of Soeharto's city arrest status
expires (on August 10)," Yahya said.
</P>
<P>
Last week Attorney General Marzuki Darusman said the dossiers
of Soeharto's case on corruption charges would be submitted to the
court in August this year.
</P>
<P>
He asked Soeharto and his family to cooperate with prosecutors
and warned them that "the security protection (for Soeharto and
his family) will be reduced to the minimum level (if they don't do
so)."
</P>
</TEXT>
