<HEADLINE> Norwegian Peace Mission Arrives in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A Norwegian peace mission, led by
Deputy Foreign Minister Raymond Johansen, arrived here Monday to
try to arrange talks between the government and the Tamil rebels,
a government official here said Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Johansen is now meeting Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman
Kadirgamar, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The peace mission includes special envoy Erik Solheim, who
leads Oslo's peace initiative in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Johansen would also meet President Chandrika Kumaratunga and
leader of the main opposition United National Party Ranil
Wickremesinghe during the three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Norway has offered to hold talks between the government and the
rebels. It appointed Solheim last month as an envoy to try and
find a way to end the 17-war in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Norway has said the current fighting would have to be resolved
before the peace initiative could proceed.
</P>
<P>
However, intense fighting is continuing on the northern Jaffna
Peninsula, with clashes on the outskirts of the Chavakachcheri
town between the government troops and the Tamil rebels who are
launching a fierce attack on troops in bid to recapture their
former stronghold in the Peninsula which they lost in may 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
