<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Interior Minister Apologizes for Anti-German Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre
Chevenement apologized on Monday for his anti-German remarks,
which have triggered an outcry of protests in French political
circles.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with television channel France II on Sunday,
Chevenement said that by presenting a proposal on building a
European federation, Germany has not been "cured of the derailment
which was Nazism."
</P>
<P>
He also accused Germany of "always dreaming of the Roman-
Germanic Holy Empire" and of "having a conception of nation of
Folks (people), which is an ethnic conception."
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply sorry that my thinking was without doubt a little
tense for the television but I see that for a certain number of
specialists of provocation, the fact of not being rallied to a
European federal project suffices to make you anti-German," said
the interior minister in a statement on television and radio
Europe I Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Former French President Valery Giscard d'Estaing said that he
was shocked by Chevenement's attack against Germany, while
Socialist Party leader Francois Hollande said that Nazism is
already a period belonging to the past of Germany.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, I love Germany, I am for Franco-German friendship.
I only said that Germany was not cured, not of Nazism, but of the
derailment which Nazism was in its history, which means that
Nazism was in my mind an accident in the German history," said
Chevenement, who is leader of the sovereignist Citizens' Movement
party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
