<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Transport Minister Decides to Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Chinese Association
(MCA) President Ling Liong Sik, who is the Transport Minister,
Monday announced his decision to retire from his cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
Ling made the announcement at the presidential council meeting
of the party, the largest Chinese-based party in Malaysia, held
here, the party's deputy president Lim Ah Lek said in a statement
issued after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The council was shocked and saddened over the sudden and
unexpected announcement, Lim said.
</P>
<P>
"The president informed the meeting that he felt that he has
served as a cabinet minister for a long time (14 years) and that
it's now the right time for him to retire," Lim said in the
statement read to the media after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Lim said the meeting unanimously and strongly appealed to Ling
to reconsider his decision as the council felt that his services
as a senior minister representing the Chinese community and the
party are irreplaceable.
</P>
<P>
"We further expressed full confidence that under his leadership,
the present problems within the party will be fully and amicably
resolved," Lim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
