<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thorpe Joins Olympic Humanitarian Aid Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- World-record swimmers Ian Thorpe
and Susie O'Neill on Monday joined Olympic Aid, a humanitarian
project created to raise funds for refugees and disadvantaged
children.
</P>
<P>
At the Olympic Aid relaunch in Sydney, founder Johann Olav Koss,
a member of the International Olympic Committee's athletes'
commission, said the cause was based on the Olympic ideals of
peace and human dignity.
</P>
<P>
Koss founded Olympic Aid in 1994 in the buildup to the
Lillehammer Winter Olympics. The program continued during the 1996
Atlanta Olympics and has so far raised about 31 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Olympic Aid is a project where Australians can make a huge
difference to the lives of children in Australia and around the
world," said Koss, a speedskater who won three gold medals at
Lillehammer.
</P>
<P>
"The money raised from the last two Olympic Games has improved
the lives and prospects of over 16 million children and enabled
the vaccination of over 12 million children."
</P>
<P>
The Australian athletes were aiming to raise 5 million
Australian dollars (2.85 millions U.S. dollars) before the
September 15-October 1 Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"Children are the world's biggest assets and, by helping them,
we can make the world a better place," said Thorpe, who set three
world records last week at the Australian Olympic selection trials
in Sydney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
