<HEADLINE> Kidnapping Ring Busted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police have smashed a major
kidnapping ring who abducted and forced women to provide sexual
services, the Ministry of Public Security said today.
</P>
<P>
To date, police have seized 13 criminal suspects and rescued
seven abducted women.
</P>
<P>
A police investigation shows that since 1996, Yang Xuerong, a
jobless resident from the Zhijiang Dong Autonomous County in
central China's Henan Province, collaborated with twelve criminal
suspects to abduct more than 20 local young girls, and sold them
as prostitutes in south China's Guangdong Province and Hainan
Province for more than one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Most of the girls are students from local nursing schools,
normal schools and technical schools. The ring leaders made
friends with these girls and later took them provinces in south
China saying that they would provide good job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Qian Xiongfei, an official with the ministry, said that as most
abducted women and children are sold to mountainous areas or
underground criminal rings in coastal areas, it's hard for police
to catch the leaders without the help of grass-root Party and
government units, local people and police units.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Security Jia Chunwang said in a recent
speech at a national tele-conference that the nationwide hunt for
traffickers of women and children is a major task for the ministry
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Statement on Cooperation in Environment, Development Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States has
signed a joint statement on the environment and development
cooperation between the two countries, the Chinese Ministry of
Science and Technology said today.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed on May 19 by Chinese Science and
Technology Minister Zhu Lilan and U.S. Ambassador to China Joseph
Prueher on behalf of their respective governments, was released by
the Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement said the two countries believe that energy
and environment constitutes one of the most important areas of
cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
"By making clean energy widely available through the
development and application of new technologies and strengthening
efforts to protect our environment and the earth's biodiversity,
China-U.S. cooperation will contribute significantly toward
further securing the welfare and quality of life of the people of
the two countries," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement was initially proposed by U.S. Vice-President Al
Gore last month in a bid to further exchanges and cooperation
between the two countries in bilateral and global environmental
protection endeavors, including protection of global climate and
biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
The statement reviewed the efforts made by both China and the
United States in energy and environment and spelt out a framework
for the future development and cooperation in these areas.
</P>
<P>
The document also reaffirmed their strong support for
international efforts to combat changes in global climate under
the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change and the
Kyoto Protocol, "in accordance with the principle of common but
differentiated responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
It also noted both China and the United States "intend to work
together and with other countries toward realizing the Kyoto
Protocol" and "assure that any increased trading will not
undermine natural resource management and special protection
programs."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
