<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Widen Campaign Against Islamic Gangs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces have stepped
up their crackdown on Islamic terrorist groups and more suspects
have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
In operations on Saturday, police killed four suspected Islamic
militants in the southern city of Adana and the biggest city of
Istanbul. Two policemen were wounded in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Police also sent seven suspects of Islamic gangs, captured in
the ongoing Operation Hope, to Ankara State Security Court (DGM) on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two suspects, recently detained for involvement in the killing
of famous secular intellectuals, told police that two Iranian
agents had planted the bombs in the murder of Ugur Mumcu, a
journalist who was assassinated in a car bomb in 1993.
</P>
<P>
But police discovered the two who planted the bombs were not
Iranian, but Turkish. They were identified as Ferhan Ozmen and
Necdet Yuksel, who have confessed to the crimes.
</P>
<P>
According to police sources, they admitted having taking part in
a string of terrorist attacks in last decade. Ozmen described many
cases, including the killing of a U.S. soldier and wounding of an
Egyptian diplomat.
</P>
<P>
He is also said to have confessed to the car-bomb killing of
Ehud Sadan, security chief at the Israeli embassy in Ankara, in
1992, as well as the wounding of Yuda Yurum, the leader of Ankara's
tiny Jewish community in a car-bomb attack in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Other Turkish victims were secular intellectuals including
journalist Mumcu, he added. According to the confessions, Ozmen
admitted that he was behind the whole series of killings.
</P>
<P>
However, the public have started to become confused as a result
of the suspects' confessions. Some people said that it was
difficult to believe that one man had done everything. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Several Jews who own private plots in the Abu Dis area have
put their properties up for sale, with a view to sell them to local
Arabs, according to sources in the Jerusalem Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The municipality is aware that the owners of some 24 dunams
(about 2.4 hectares) are already negotiating to sell their land, as
the government prepares to hand full control of Abu Dis and its
environs to the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Of the 300 dunams (about 30 hectares) of Jewish-owned land
around Abu Dis, 100 (about 10 hectares) are held by the Jewish
National Fund. Of this, the Jerusalem Municipality is looking to
build 200 apartments on a plot. The remaining 176 dunams (about 17.
6 hectares) of privately owned land are as yet not for sale.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel has expressed reserved satisfaction with the results
of the United Nations conference on the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty (NPT), which closed in New York on Saturday. Israel did not
take part in the conference or send an observer.
</P>
<P>
Sources in Jerusalem say the United States prevented the
conference from taking any measures against Israel and thus
fulfilled its commitment to the understandings reached between
Washington and Israel on the subject.
</P>
<P>
In the concluding remarks, Israel was mentioned for the first
time as the only country in the Middle East that has not signed the
NPT. However, the U.S. and Egypt reached an "arrangement" that no
substantive measures would be taken against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli military sources are worrying that the events of the
past few days signal the impending collapse of the Israeli-backed
South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
As many as 40 SLA soldiers and their families abandoned their
outposts in the central sector of the Israeli-occupied buffer zone
in south Lebanon Sunday, after masses of Lebanese Shiite residents
returned to their homes in the region, according to unconfirmed
reports from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The SLA soldiers reported that they took most of the arms with
them when they left the Taiben outpost, which was transferred to
them by the Israeli army just a week ago, but it is not clear what
happened to an armored personnel carrier and tank stationed there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a wave of defections by Shiite soldiers has swept
through the ranks of the SLA in recent weeks, with the Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas claiming that dozens have defected.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday suspended the
back-channel negotiations with the Palestinians in Stockholm and
ordered the Israeli team home, due to the ongoing violence in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Team leader and Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami
and negotiator Gilad Sher are expected to be back on Monday.
Barak's spokesman Gadi Baltiansky said the situation must be
reviewed before the talks can resume.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israelis and tourists have been barred from entering
the Palestinian self-rule city of Jericho, following a firebomb
attack on an Israeli car traveling through the city early Sunday
morning, en route to the Golan Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
