<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Ruling Coalition Expected to Be Restored Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung's
nomination of Lee Han-dong as prime minister is seen as a first
step to restore the ruling coalition between his Millennium
Democratic Party (MDP) and the minor United Liberal Democrats (ULD)
.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of the coalition is unavoidable destiny, Lee,
who is ULD president, said at a press conference after his
nomination Monday morning to succeed Park Tae-jung, who resigned
last weekend over tax evasion scandal.
</P>
<P>
President Kim will meet ULD founder Kim Jong-pil for restoring
the coalition ahead of the inter-Korean summit. As far as national
security is concerned, Kim Jong-pil wants a supra-partisan
approach to the matter, said the prime minster-designate.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, it was none other than Lee Han-dong who declared
the breakup to the coalition before the general elections on April
13 this year, and accused President Kim of failing to practice the
cabinet system agreed by the two parties ahead of the presidential
election in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1997 agreement, President Kim promised to carry out
the cabinet system after two years in office.
</P>
<P>
Designating Lee as new prime minister, President Kim is
believed to have taken into account Lee's role in restoring the
ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Lee will become the third prime minister of the Kim Dae-jung
government after Kim Jong-pil and Park Tae-joon from the ULD if
the South Korean parliament approves the nomination.
</P>
<P>
To maximize his political role, Lee is expected to push for an
early restoration of the broken relations between President Kim
and ULD founder Kim Jong-pil.
</P>
<P>
However, some ULD members are strongly opposed to restoring the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
ULD Vice President Kim Jong-ho said the designation of Lee as
prime minister is an issue different from the restoration of
relations between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the major opposition Grand National Party (GNP) is
attacking the designation as a "plot to artificially reorganize
the political landscape."
</P>
<P>
If the coalition is successfully restored between the MDP with
119 parliament members and the ULD with 17, it can obtain a razor-
thin majority in the 273-member South Korean parliament.
</P>
<P>
The GNP, which now enjoys a parliamentary majority with 133
seats, has called for hearing on the nomination, warning that Lee'
s approval as prime minister is impossible without a hearing.
</P>
<P>
A new round of political struggle is feared to surface in the
new National Assembly, observers here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
