<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Filmmakers Prepare for WTO Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese filmmakers have urged
that more efforts need be taken to enable their products to become
more competitive when the country joins the WTO.
</P>
<P>
They worry that the industry might be further eclipsed by
American blockbusters when China opens a bigger market to the
international movie world
</P>
<P>
"The job is imperative," said Wei Yuming, a leading filmmaker
with the Changchun Film Studio, the cradle of the country's movie
industry.
</P>
<P>
The studio shut down its special effects workshop in 1992 when
it ran out of money. There are only about 10 experienced special
effects technicians in the country, according to Wei.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of American movies such as "Titanic," "Twister"
and "Jurassic Park" can be largely attributed to computer-aided
special effects. All these films have been shown in China and
lured a huge number of Chinese viewers.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of a special effects workshop will cost at
least 10 million yuan (1.2 million U.S. dollars), a figure which
is beyond the means of China's sluggish movie industry, said Wei.
</P>
<P>
However, filmmakers say that they welcome China's entry into
the WTO because globalization is a general trend.
</P>
<P>
China's film authorities decided last month that the reform and
upgrading of film making technologies should be one of the ten
tasks the film industry will do in the near future.
</P>
<P>
A special effects department will also be established in the
Beijing Film College to train experts who will be able to thrive
in a competitive market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt-to-Equity Swap Deals Help Beijing's State Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Another 12 state-owned enterprises
in Beijing have signed debt-to-equity swap deals to get themselves
out of financial difficulties and improve their performance,
adding the total number such enterprises to 16.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16.62 billion yuan of debts have been converted into
share-holding rights owned by banks, accounting for about 94.5
percent of the total amount approved by the municipal economic and
trade commission for swap deals.
</P>
<P>
These swap deals have greatly deepen the reform of China's
state-owned enterprises, since the lessened debt burden allows
these companies in backbone industries to adjust their product mix
and realize better growth, according to a municipal official in
charge of local enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
The debt-to-equity swap is adopted as a measure to revitalize
China's state-owned enterprises, the backbone of the national
economy. So far the country's four big commercial banks have all
set up asset management companies aimed at dealing with the
problem of bad debts from state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Under the swap program, after bad debts from enterprises are
converted into equity and state-owned enterprises begin to perform
better economically, asset management companies will either list
the enterprises concerned or have the enterprises buy the equity
back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0198 </DOCNO>
