<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Should Concern Deflation: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Deflation, rather than inflation,
should be China's principal policy concern, according to a United
Nations report released here today.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices are estimated to have fallen by 1.4 percent in
1999 after a fall of 0.8 percent in 1998, said the report on the
Economic and Social Survey of Asia and the Pacific 2000 launched
by the UN Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific
(ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
In China deflation is a manifestation of weak consumer
confidence occasioned by business uncertainty and associated job
insecurity. Households have reacted to this by increasing savings,
the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Prices are expected to stop declining in 2000 with the increase
in oil and other commodity prices. Whether this counters the high
propensity to save of Chinese households remains to be seen, the
report noted.
</P>
<P>
The report said that consumer expenditure is still weak in
China, and the situation needs to change soon if fiscal deficits
are to become a sustainable burden.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Economy Growing Rapidly: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The economy of developing nations
in Asia and the Pacific is expected to grow around six percent
this year, 0.5 percentage points more than the increase of last
year, according to a United Nations report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The world economy led by strong growth in the U.S., higher
growth in the European Union and tentative signs of recovery in
Japan is estimated to have grown by 2.6 percent in 1999, said the
report on the Economic and Social Survey of Asia and the Pacific
2000 launched by the UN Economic and Social Commission for Asia
and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Both developed and developing economies have performed better
than expected in 1999, the report said, adding that the economic
growth of Asia-Pacific developing countries represents a
remarkable turnaround from the virtually zero growth experienced
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Higher growth in Asia-Pacific developing countries was the
combined result of fiscal stimuli and buoyant exports. These two
factors were particularly evident in the crisis-hit economies of
the region. The growth has been achieved in an environment of
lower inflation.
</P>
<P>
This, in turn, led to enhanced business and household
confidence, higher stock markets, exchange rate stability and a
moderate recovery of external capital flows, according to the
report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
