<HEADLINE> Estrada Orders to Tighten Security in Wake of Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday the intelligence and law enforcement communities are
working hard to determine the perpetrators behind the bomb blast
that hit a shopping mall here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said in a radio speech that
the police have orders from President Joseph Estrada to heighten
security measures to prevent a repeat of the incident, which
occurred at the SM Megamall Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The president ordered the Philippine National Police and Armed
Forces of the Philippines to heighten security measures," Mercado
said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the public to practice vigilance on their part,
saying the perpetrators might strike even outside malls. "We all
have to be very security conscious," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, national police head Panfilo Lacson said he is
taking a direct hand in the incident by having the Presidential
Anti-Organized Crime Task Force (PAOTF) participate in the
investigation of the mall blast.
</P>
<P>
Lacson said he ordered the PAOCTF to set aside its other
pending intelligence assignments and focus on the SM Megamall
bombing.
</P>
<P>
He said the bombing could have been the handiwork of the rebel
group of the New People's Army, adding that the Central Police
District of Manila is questioning eight suspects in the bombing
incident.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, SM Megamall, the biggest shopping center in the
country, tightened its security of incoming shoppers, resulting in
long queues at the SM's entrances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
