<HEADLINE> Tension Continues Between Ugandan, Rwandan Army in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Tension has remained high in
Kisangani, causing fears of a fresh outbreak of clashes between
Ugandan and Rwandan armies in the northeast city of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), the New Vision daily reported here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have agreed to demilitarize the city after
their troops clashed on May 5 and 8. They have also agreed to
withdraw their troops to a distance of 100 kilometers out of the
city and leave only companies of 200 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Rwanda-backed Goma rebels of the
Congolese Rally of Democracy (RCD) are also to withdraw. But
RCD-Goma's Military Commander Jean Pierre Ondekane said his forces
would not withdraw, according to the New Vision report.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement to demilitarize is null and void if the Goma
group does not pull out," Sula Semakula, Ugandan army commander in
Kisangani, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda army chiefs said the situation in Kisangani
is unavoidably hostile, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said James Baxter, chief of staff of the U.N. Observer
Mission in the DRC, attempted to bring Semakula and his Rwandan
counterpart to a round table, but he failed twice last week.
</P>
<P>
Bangoka International Airport, controlled by the Uganda
People's Defence Forces (UPDF), is being besieged by the Rwanda
Patriotic Army (RPA) who have dug-in along the southern and
eastern sides of the runway, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It added that the rival armies are separated only by a
100-meter runway.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Patrick Kiyingi, commander of UPDF's 9th
battalion, as saying that the situation is tense and fighting may
re-erupted anytime.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda troops supported rival rebel groups to fight
against DRC President Laurent Kabila's government in a less than
two-year conflict which also drew Zimbabwean, Angolan and Namibian
forces on Kabila's side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
