<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Curbs Desertification for Beijing's Safety (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- An emergency anti-desertification
program has been launched in Inner Mongolia to ensure ecological
safety of China's capital of Beijing and the nearby port city
Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Twelve major duststorms have swept North China this year,
including Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The emergency program covers three deserts, one of which is
just 180 kilometers away from Beijing, and moving toward the
capital at an annual pace of 1.8 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the countries most seriously affected by desert
expansion. Its deserts currently cover 2.62 million square
kilometers or 27 percent of its territory, mainly located in China
's northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Sandstorms this year have alarmed the central authorities.
</P>
<P>
During a recent inspection tour to Hebei Province and Inner
Mongolia, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji called for immediate and
efficient efforts to combat serious desertification in the country
and to build greenbelts to improve the environment.
</P>
<P>
He called on governments at all levels and the masses to act
immediately to work for a better environment for the benefit of
China and its younger generations.
</P>
<P>
Over-grazing by cattle and sheep is also a major cause of
desertification in China's northern and western regions, he noted,
and urged efficient protection and supervision of the grasslands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Curbs Desertification for Beijing's Safety (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu also pledged that the central government increase financial
support to Hebei and Inner Mongolia for their efforts to combat
water and soil erosion as well as financial aid for new forests.
</P>
<P>
Related government departments are also taking steps to tackle
desertification.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Forestry Administration, China could
curb desertification as early as 2010. By 2050, authorities "may
be able to bring all of China's deserts under control in a bid to
ensure harmonious development of China's economy, society and
environment."
</P>
<P>
If these measures are successful, the area covered by deserts
would no longer expand 2,460 square kilometers per year in China,
as it is happening now, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology and the Ministry of
Agriculture have also worked out plans to prevent desert expansion
and grass planting.
</P>
<P>
In the past fifty years, the Chinese government has never given
up its battle against desertification. Three sand-shield belts
were built in northern Beijing, and programs to curb soil erosion
have been launched across the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 12 percent of deserts have been reclaimed,
and 11 million hectares of deteriorated grassland was protected or
recovered over the last five decades in China.
</P>
<P>
However, the recovery rate is still behind increasing
desertification in the country. "We still need to work much harder
in this respect," experts claim.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
