<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Central Bank Not to Take Sides in Currency Union Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Reserve Bank
Governor Don Brash said Monday in Auckland that as New Zealand's
central bank, his bank would not be taking sides in the debate
about whether New Zealand should join a currency union with
Australia or the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Auckland Rotary Club, Brash said: "Entering a
currency union is a major foreign policy decision, and thus a
matter for elected politicians. It is not a matter on which a
central banker should express an overall opinion," according to a
press release issued here by the Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
He told the gathering that: "Currency union is not a magic path
to substantially faster New Zealand growth. It is no substitute
for domestic policies that promote stronger productivity growth.
It is not an issue which should be decided in haste. And it is not
an issue on which the Reserve Bank will be taking sides."
</P>
<P>
For the past year and more, there has been a debate among New
Zealand politicians, economists and traders about a currency union
with Australia or the United States. But the New Zealand
government either with the National Party or the Labor Party as
its ruling party has repeatedly made it clear that the issue is
not on its agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
