<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gov't to Aid Frozen Food Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government decided to
waive 80 percent interest on the bank loans of the frozen food
factories affected by the 1997 EU ban and 1998 devastating floods
to energize this potential export sector, The Financial Express
reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, the owners of the factories affected
by the adversities during the two years while remaining in
operation will pay 20 percent of the interest for those two years,
while the government and concerned banks will bear the rest in
equal shares.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken Sunday at a high-level meeting on
resolving the problems faced by the frozen food export sector,
which was presided by Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria.
</P>
<P>
A meeting source said with the partial exemption the owners are
expected to get relief from liabilities worth nearly 900 million
taka(17 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nearly 55 frozen food factories were affected by the import ban
slapped by the European Union in 1997 and the devastating floods
in 1998. Most of them were also overburdened by damage in the 1991
cyclone.
</P>
<P>
"The frozen food export sector is making important contribution
to the country's economy," said the finance minister while
addressing the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for boosting export of frozen foods, Kibria
assured all possible assistance for the foreign exchange-earning
sector, which fetches around 3 billion taka (58 million dollars)
annually in export earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
