<HEADLINE> S. Lanka's Tea Export Increases in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's tea export earnings
recorded an increase of 17 percent to 12 billion rupees (165
million U.S. dollars) during the first quarter this year over the
same period last year, a tea brokering firm said in a latest
market report.
</P>
<P>
According to the market report of John Keels, the average price
of a kilogram of tea increased by 11.8 percent to 180 rupees (2.47
dollars) during the first three months this year.
</P>
<P>
The export volume also increased by 11.67 percent to 67 million
kilograms over the same period in 1999, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said the biggest importers were Commonwealth of Independent
States countries with 15 million kilograms, followed by the United
Arab Emirates with 10 million kilograms, Turkey 6 million
kilograms and Syria 4 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka also recorded the highest ever production figures for
the first quarter with 76.5 million kilograms, six percent
increase over the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, India had the biggest tea crop of 807 million
kilograms,followed by Sri Lanka with 284 million kilograms and
Kenya 249 million kilograms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
