<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation Still Tense in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to reports reaching here Monday, explosions of hand-
made bombs and grenades were still heard on Sunday night, breaking
the silence at nights in the Ahuru Karang Panjang area and other
areas prone to conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Streets in the Mardika and Batu Merah areas were still blocked
with barbed wire, rocks and logs, causing traffic to move slowly.
Some youths armed with sharp and pointed weapons guarded their
neighborhood anticipating intrusions by certain groups aiming at
disturbing peace.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Pattimura Military Command overseeing Maluku
Brig. Gen. Max Tamaela has extended the curfew from 21:00 to 05:00
a.m.
</P>
<P>
He said 200 troops reinforcements from Sriwijaya's 141 Infantry
Battalion arrived in Ambon on Sunday noon by Hercules military
transport airplane from Palembang, South Sumatera.
</P>
<P>
"We warn the warring camps not to attack each other. Leave the
mobs or groups of rioters to us. If they want to help, they may
guard their own neighborhoods. All groups, including Laskar Jihad
(Jihad Force), could face the wrath of the troops if they do not
stop the fighting," he was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have said there are strong indications that the
Laskar Jihad, who have sneaked an estimated 2,200 volunteers into
Ambon, are behind the latest wave of violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at least 16 Dutch and French people have asked
Maluku Governor Saleh Latuconsina and Tamaela to help evacuate
them from Ambon, about 2,500 kilometers northeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are representatives of nongovernmental
organizations which have helped the local administration in
distributing humanitarian aid and building health facilities for
the refugees.
</P>
<P>
"We do not like it, but we understand their wish, especially in
view of the security condition here (Ambon). But they promise to
return once the situation gets better," Latuconsina was quoted by
the Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Maluku has witnessed a year-long ethnic bloodshed between
Christians and Muslims, which has claimed more than 1,300 civilian
lives. Clashes have subsided in recent months but tension remains
in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Last week's violence is the first major eruption of violence in
Ambon this month. On April 30 six people were killed and more than
10 others injured near Ambon's port and at least 40 houses were
razed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
