<HEADLINE> China Discovers 14th Century Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Some blunderbusses made in the 14th
century were recently discovered in Nanjing, capital of east China
's coastal province Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
The firearms, unearthed in a construction site near the
Tongjimen area of Nanjing, were made in 1373, according to the
markings on them.
</P>
<P>
The blunderbusses are 45 cm in length, and with the bores
taking two thirds of the length, the firearms could have stronger
shooting capacity than others of the same kind.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the well-crafted weapons represent the highest
level of firearm-making technology at that time in China.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing then was the capital and the economic and technological
center of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
