<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nets Wins NBA Draft Lottery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The New Jersey Nets won the
National Basketball Association draft lottery on Sunday, earning
the right to make the No. 1 overall pick next month.
</P>
<P>
The Nets, who fired coach Don Casey after missing the playoffs
with a 31-51 record and then had president Michael Rowe resign,
had only a 4.4 percent chance of winning the ping-pong ball
lottery.
</P>
<P>
But unlike their injury plagued season, they got lucky.
</P>
<P>
The entire lottery was somewhat of an upset as Vancouver jumped
to second in the selection order.
</P>
<P>
The Los Angeles Clippers, who had the worst record in the
league at 15-67, got the third pick.
</P>
<P>
Chicago, which won the lottery last year, also slipped despite
having the second worst record (17-65) in the league. They will
draft fourth and be followed by Orlando, which will have three
picks in the draft - fifth, 10th and 13th.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta will pick sixth and will be followed by Chicago - using
a pick it got from Washington, Cleveland, Houston, Orlando, Boston,
Dallas and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second time the Nets will have the No. 1 pick.
They had it in 1990 and took Derrick Coleman, currently with the
Charlotte Hornets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
