<HEADLINE> Erekat Calls for More International Efforts to Resume Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat on Monday urged the international community to exert every
possible effort to bring the Middle East peace process back on
track.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was contained in messages to U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan, U.S. Middle East special envoy Dennis Ross, European
Union Mideast envoy Miguel Moratinos as well as representatives of
the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Erekat called on the world leaders to help restore the
credibility of the peace process through urging relevant parties to
implement the signed accords, sincerely and accurately.
</P>
<P>
In a similar message to his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran,
Erekat underscored the necessity of Israel's commitment to carrying
out the third redeployment by June 23.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are still waiting for Israel's response to the
name list of Palestinian prisoners who should be released under the
Sharm el Sheikh memorandum signed last September, he told Eran.
Erekat made the appeal one day after Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak called his negotiation team in Stockholm for talks with the
Palestinians to return home in light of the surge of violence in
the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The two days of violent demonstrations in West Bank and Gaza
Strip reportedly led to the killing of one Palestinian and wounding
of about 160 people. One Israeli solider was seriously wounded by
Palestinian gunfire and five others slightly wounded by stones.
</P>
<P>
The weekend Days of Rage was declared by the Palestinian
National Authority to press for the release of 1,650 Palestinian
prisoners held by Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
