<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Security Cabinet Convenes to Discuss Lebanon Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
convened his security cabinet Monday evening to discuss the rapidly
deteriorating situation in south Lebanon and its effects on Israeli
army's planned withdrawal from the region.
</P>
<P>
Although the outcome of the inner-circle meeting is not
announced, Israel media has speculated Barak and his policy-making
ministers will explore the possibility to speed up the Lebanon
withdrawal, which was originally set to be carried out before July.
</P>
<P>
It is possible now that the redeployment will advance to early
June, or even the coming days, some analysts predicted.
</P>
<P>
The possibility arised following the sudden change of the
situation in the security zone in south Lebanon, which was set up
by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed aim to protect its north from
cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
In March, the Israeli cabinet approved Barak's proposal to
withdraw from the zone by July and end its two-decade occupation in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In order to carry out the cabinet decision, Israel Defense
Forces (IDF) had transferred several outposts in the buffer zone to
its proxy militia South Lebanon Army (SLA) during the past few
weeks, hoping the militant group would act as buffer forces in the
zone for some time.
</P>
<P>
However, the outposts were in turn abandoned on Monday by SLA
militiamen, who deserted their position to seek asylum in Israel or
to defect to the approaching Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas with a
snowslide style in less than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The disorderly SLA disassembly has created such a situation that
there is no longer a territorial continuity under Israeli control
in the security zone, with Hezbollah taking over most fortified
outposts in the central sector of the zone.
</P>
<P>
The situation change is really not in Israel's direction as
Israel had hoped that within the framework of relevant United
Nations Security Council Resolutions, the peacekeeping U.N. Interim
Forces in Lebanon (UNIFIL) will fill the security vacuum left by
IDF soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Barak reportedly had telephone conversations with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, U.S. Secretary of State Madelaine
Albright and French President Jacques Chirac on Monday, obviously
exchanging opinions with these leaders about further steps the
International community should take in the context of such a
situation out of control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, IDF Northern Commander Gabi Ashkenazi clarified at a
press conference Monday evening that no final date has been decided
for the planned withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that even the events that took place Monday were
among the many possible scenarios IDF had predicted, and the army
has not by any means lost control.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, there were media reports that Israeli army had
received orders from Barak to be ready for redeployment to the
international border between Israel and Lebanon as early as June 1,
five weeks ahead of the July deadline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
