<HEADLINE> Protestant Leader Campaigns for N.Irish Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's main pro-British
Protestant leader David Trimble is facing a crucial week as he
sets about convincing his colleagues to restore the power-sharing
executive in the province.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist Party leader Trimble now has less than a week
to convince the 860-member Ulster Unionist Council, before their
meeting on Saturday, that the Irish Republican Army offer to put
its arms beyond use is genuine.
</P>
<P>
He said in Belfast on Monday that if his party voted against
accepting the package of proposals to restart devolution,unionism
would be consigned to the political wilderness.
</P>
<P>
If the party refuses to accept his position of putting the
offer from republicans to the test by going back into a government
including Sinn Fein, his leadership could be in doubt.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Trimble said he believed the IRA's campaign of
violence was finally over.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not saying that the future's going to be entirely free of
violence. I think that the organized, coherent campaign that the
IRA operated for 30 years is not going to come back again,"he said.
</P>
<P>
"There may be problems, there may still be violence, and the
violence may come from dissident elements. It may even come from
elements within the IRA. What I am saying is that the major,
organized campaign has gone because... it was beaten," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sinn Fein said the IRA initiative to "put its
weapons beyond use" is now at risk following what the party views
as concessions to Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
A Sinn Fein spokesman said Monday the republicans were
extremely concerned that unionist acceptance of the current
package put forward by the governments to return Northern Ireland'
s power-sharing executive would be conditional. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
