<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes a Peaceful Israeli Withdrawal from South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON. May 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on Monday
that Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon is in compliance with
U.N. resolution 425 and urged Arabs to let Israel withdraw
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"No one should be raising any question about that ... There is
no reason not to support it and there is no justification for
violence to be directed against it," U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis
Ross said at gathering of American supporters of Israel in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Israel started its withdrawal on Monday and reports said there
were in near chaos following the pullout with Shiite Muslim
guerrillas and their supporters rushed in to reclaim villages held
by Israel forces for two decades.
</P>
<P>
The takeover was peaceful at first, with little resistance from
the Israeli allied militiamen. But it turned bloody when battle
tanks fired artillery shells and an Israeli helicopter gunship
strafed the area, apparently in an effort to scare away the
approaching civilians.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who returned from Israeli-Palestinian peace talks last
week, also spoke about the violence of the past few days between
Israeli troops and Palestinians, including some armed Palestinian
policemen in uniform, saying that violence should not play a part
in negotiations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"You can't have negotiations that are going to succeed in an
environment that is characterized by violence. It simply doesn't
work," he said. "There will not be an agreement that is forged
through the street or through violence. There will only be an
agreement if it is done at the negotiating table."
</P>
<P>
On Syrian-Israeli track, in abeyance since a session in West
Virginia in January, Ross said the gaps were not very wide but the
process was "very brittle."
</P>
<P>
"We are at a point where the door has not been closed on trying
to reach an agreement ... But at the end of the day the parties
themselves are going to be the ones who have to walk through the
door together," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States won't overcome the differences ... A go-
between can help get things to the point where the two parties
themselves resolve the differences but only the two parties
dealing directly will overcome the gaps," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
