<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Release of Fiji Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
warned Fiji's gunmen of "substantial consequences" for
international relations if they do not release the island nation's
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to decide an internal political question," State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher said at a briefing. "On the
other hand ... this poor guy's being held, and the first thing
that ought to happen is he ought to be released. And at that point,
any political process in Fiji is up to them."
</P>
<P>
Fijian Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry has been held by gunmen
since Friday by Coup leader George Speight, who said he was acting
on behalf of indigenous Fijians.
</P>
<P>
Boucher stressed the importance of Chaudry's release and the
maintenance of constitutional order.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly there are consequences of any unconstitutional seizure
of power," Boucher said. "There would be very substantial
consequences for U.S.- Fiji relations, very detrimental to Fiji's
standing in the international community.
</P>
</TEXT>
