<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Determined to Get All Detainees Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Annan urged the RUF to end hostile acts and fully cooperate "in
retrieving the dead, wounded and missing", while appealing to
those with influence with the RUF to continue to work towards this
objective, Eckhard told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
A new batch of 54 military personnel of the U.N. Mission in
Sierra Leone (UNAMSIL) was released Sunday night. They include 42
Zambians, 10 Kenyans and two military observers, one each from
Malaysia and Norway, Eckhard announced.
</P>
<P>
Annan hoped that more U.N. detainees would be freed this week.
</P>
<P>
Over 500 UNAMSIL personnel had been taken hostage since the
beginning of may. Most of them are Zambians. RFU's action followed
a dispute between it and the U.N. peacekeepers over disarmament
under the July 7, 1999 peace agreement to end the 9-year war in
the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Annan recommended that the UNAMSIL force strength be raised to
16,500 from the current 13,000. A further expansion may be needed
to establish security throughout the country, disarm rebel
fighters and eventually hold elections, he said in his latest
report on Sierra Leone released Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan also suggested that the Security Council
consider a strengthening of the sanctions regime to prevent RUF
commanders from reaping the benefits of their illegal exploitation
of mineral resources, in particular diamonds.
</P>
<P>
At a press encounter Monday, the U.N. chief expressed his
dissatisfaction over U.S. Senator Judd Gregg's hold on U.S. peace-
keeping funds, calling it "disruptive" to the U.N. peace-keeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
In a foreign policy dispute with the U.S. administration,
Chairman of the Senate Appropriations Subcommittee Gregg has
blocked the government from paying its dues to the U.N. for peace-
keeping missions in Congo, Kosovo, East Timor and Sierra Leone.
</P>
</TEXT>
