<HEADLINE> Arkansas Supreme Court Panel Recommends Disbarment of Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A Supreme Court Committee of
Arkansas State in the United States has recommended that President
Clinton be disbarred because of "serious misconduct".
</P>
<P>
A majority of committee members, who met Friday to consider two
complaints against the president, suggested that President Clinton
be disciplined for false testimony about his relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, the Supreme Court said
Monday in releasing the committee recommendation.
</P>
<P>
Under the rules of the Committee of Professional Conduct, the
disbarment recommendation now goes to the Circuit Court in Little
Rock for consideration.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the court, the committee's executive director
said Clinton's behavior in the Lewinsky case "constituted serious
misconduct" in violation of state rules governing lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who has been a lawyer for more than 25 years, has not
practiced law since the early 1980s. He was governor from 1979 to
1981 and again from 1983 until he was elected president in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
