<HEADLINE> Europe's Markets Hit By Plunge on Wall St. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) - Europe's major stock markets closed
sharply lower Monday as technology, media and telecom stocks again
came under pressure after the latest tech-led sell-off in US
markets.
</P>
<P>
London's stocks ended a thin, volatile session little changed
as steep losses in troubled tech stocks were offset by Gains in
banks, oil companies and cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
It's benchmark FTSE 100 index slipped 9.9 points, or 0.1
percent, to 6035.5, with "old economy" retailing and tobacco
stocks buoying the markets.
</P>
<P>
A 14.2 percent plunge made hand-held computer maker Psion fell
14.2 percent the FTSE 100's biggest faller, followed by chip
designer ARM Holdings with a 10.6 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Telewest, one of Britain's biggest cable companies, lost 3
percent and regional telecom operator Kingston Communications
dropped 9.7 percent as a new bout of nerves wiped out early gains
by some telecom and technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
Person, the world's largest education publisher fell 4.2
percent, British Sky Broadcasting dropped 7 percent, and financial
data and news firm Reuters Group lost 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt shed 76 points, or 1.1 percent, to
6912.96, with banking stocks losing ground on the prospect of
higher regional interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Paris' benchmark CAC-40 index ended down 101.88 or 1.64 percent
at 6094.17 points, with gains outpacing decliners 21-19.  
</P>
</TEXT>
