<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Peace between Eritrea, Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is immensely saddened at the resumption
of what is an increasingly incomprehensible war. There can be no
justification for such large scale death and suffering, especially
at time when both countries are wracked by drought and hunger,"
Annan's spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
The two-year war between Eritrea and Ethiopia stemming from a
border dispute has caused thousands of deaths on both sides.
Peace efforts by the U.N., the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
and regional countries have failed to produce tangible results.
</P>
<P>
There is no indication that the renewed fighting, which erupted
on May 12, will end immediately despite the Council's arms
sanctions against them.
</P>
<P>
The drought in the Horn of Africa is now affecting over 650,000
people in war-torn Ethiopia and Eritrea, U.N. statistics show.
</P>
<P>
International peace efforts led by the OAU is continuing and
Annan fully supports the peace efforts, Eckhard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
