<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Shocked at Mutilated Bodies in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite uncertainty about the bodies belonging to U.N.
peacekeepers, Annan was "appalled by the culture of violence and
cruelty which pervades the conflict in Sierra Leone", the
spokesman stated.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief called on all parties to respect fully
international humanitarian law and recognized standards of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the continuing efforts by regional leaders will
lead to the expeditious and unconditional release of all U.N.
personnel detained by the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peace-keeping mission, now numbering 13,000 in the
west African nation is to monitor the implementation of a peace
accord signed last July between the RUF and the government to end
the 9-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
Over 500 U.N. peace-keepers have been taken hostage since the
beginning of May. The RUF's action followed a dispute between it
and the U.N. personnel over disarmament under the peace agreement.
About half of the detainees are still in RUF's hands.
</P>
<P>
U.N.peace-keepers couldn't identify the corps wearing U.N.
uniforms as the rebels often stripped many of the captive peace-
keepers of their weapons and uniforms, and took them for their own
use, U.N. sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
