<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Globalization to Drive Consolidation Among Auto Manufacturers, Suppliers, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGLES, May 22 (Xinhua) -- There may be just eight
independent global vehicle manufacturer groups by 2010, down from
16 today, and this will drive further globalization and
consolidation of their suppliers, according to a report released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
And this trend will fundamentally change relationships between
suppliers and manufacturers and create new opportunities for the
survivors, said the report from Roland Berger &AMP; Partners, an
international management consulting firm of European origin with
offices in 22 countries.
</P>
<P>
The firm interviewed 70 representatives from automakers and
suppliers around the world to determine the impact of major "mega-
trends" on suppliers and their relationships with their customers.
</P>
<P>
Ten years from now, the report said, fewer than 50 "mega-
supplier groups" will compete for large, global platform contracts,
take on greater risks for a vehicle's ultimate success and assume
significantly more responsibility for systems integration and sub-
supplier management.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, vehicle-volume growth in major markets
such as the United States may slow down in the near future, but
suppliers still will have the chance to increase revenues by
providing additional value-added content, primarily through
technological innovation that improve safety, reduce weight, boost
fuel economy, enhance component performance, improve driver and
occupant functionality as well as comfort.
</P>
<P>
The study forecasts that electronics will drive 90 percent of
all future innovation in the automobile and that by 2010
electronics will account for a third of vehicle cost, a jump of
more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The share of value-added content contributed by automakers to
every vehicle will steadily decline to little more than 25 percent
by 2010, with suppliers picking up the difference.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, e-commerce will shake the supply chain. As
automakers are moving rapidly toward Internet-based platforms for
their supplier relationships, suppliers must act responsively,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the report said, there will be three to five top
suppliers for each module or system, down from seven or eight
today. This level of consolidation already exists in seat, brake
and safety systems. Meanwhile, the number of modules or systems
per vehicle will shrink to about ten, from 18 to 20 today.
</P>
<P>
These trends will have a direct impact on suppliers' core
profitability, the report said. Supplier firms will be forced to
sharpen their focus in key areas including customer relations,
innovation, cost, integration, global delivery, and management of
cooperative ventures and merger or acquisition activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
