<HEADLINE> Mexico Goes Up to 13th Place in World Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 22 (Xinhua)-- Mexico went up in recent years
from 4th to 13th position in world trade due to its free trade
accords, especially that made with United States and Canada, said
an analyst on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mexico went up from place 17 in 1993 to 13 in 1999 and will
reach 12 in year 2003, said economist Alfredo Coutino of American
finance studies firm Wharton Econometrics, in an analysis
divulged Monday by the press.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's always greater production apparatus integrating to
North America's economic zone was determinant for the country's
rise in global trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
The North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) in force since
1994 with United States and Canada, marked Mexico's globalization,
said Coutino, director of Macroeconomic Analysis for Mexico of
this American firm.
</P>
<P>
Mexico increased by 300 percent its exports and doubled its
imports since NAFTA's application and increased its taking in of
outside direct investments, from 4.4 billion dollars in 1993 to 11
billion in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is the Latin American country with greatest number of
free trade agreements, including those in force and those signed
with other countries in the region and with European Union and
Israel -which are pending application-, and is negotiating
agreement with Singapore in Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
