<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall in Second Consecutive Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell in the
second consecutive session Monday as investors worried about lower
corporate profits because of higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 84.30 at 10,542.55,
extending its loss of 150.43 points Friday. The blue chip index
fell as much as 250 points during the session.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 26.19 at 3,364.
21. The composite hit 3,172.65 before the late hour rally, marking
a new intraday low for 2000.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 6.23 at 1,400.72.
</P>
<P>
The market plunged as investors moved away from the tech stocks
as well as industrial shares in fears that corporate earnings will
be hurt by rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Federal Reserve raised interest rates
aggressively for the sixth time since last June to keep inflation
at bay and warned investors of more hike in rates in the future.
Higher rates have hit the stock market heavily.
</P>
<P>
The big names of Intel, Cisco Systems and Oracle all fell,
driving the Nasdaq index lower. General Motors led the Dow's
falling.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 4.63 at 634.92 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 10.40 at 903.63. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 8.04 at 471.67.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the new York Stock Exchange, with 1,772 down, 1,179 up and 430
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 863.16 million shares from 850.51
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000522.0357 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Meet in Annan's Report on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council is scheduled to have a late night meeting Monday to
discuss U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's report on reinforcing
U.N. forces in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan submitted a report to the Security Council earlier today,
recommending that the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (
UNIFIL) be reinforced in order to carry out its responsibilities
under Resolution 425 of 1978.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the total troop strength for carrying out the tasks
related to confirming the withdrawal of Israeli troops would thus
increase from the present Level of 4,513 to approximately 5,600.
</P>
<P>
Once the Israeli withdrawal is confirmed and if the security
situation permits, the force of UNIFIL would have to be
immediately increased to 7,935 personnel.
</P>
<P>
The report also contains the minimum conditions and
requirements which must be met if resolution 425 is to be
implemented fully and without conditions and if the United Nations
is to be in a position to fulfill its responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the conclusion of Council's
meeting in the afternoon, Russian Ambassador to the United Nations,
Sergey Lavrov, said the Council will have further discussions on
the report this night and a draft resolution is expected to be
voted Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Israel has informed the United Nations in April that it will
complete withdrawal of all its troops from southern Lebanon by
July.
</P>
<P>
Resolution 425 of 1978 established two requirements. First, the
Security Council called for "strict respect for the territorial
integrity, sovereignty and political independence of Lebanon
within its internationally recognized boundaries. And second, the
Security Council called upon Israel"immediately to cease its
military action against Lebanese territorial integrity and
withdraw its forces from all Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also decided "in the light of the request
of the Government of Lebanon, to establish immediately a United
Nations Interim Force for Southern Lebanon aimed at three purposes:
confirming the withdrawal of Israeli troops, restoring
international peace and security and assisting the Government of
Lebanon in ensuring the return of its effective authority in the
area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
